const PRESET_LESSONS = [
  // ==================== A1 ====================
  { id:"a1-01", level:"A1", title:"My Family", text:"I have a small family. There are four people. My father, my mother, my sister, and me. My father is tall. He works in an office. My mother is kind. She cooks very well. My sister is young. She likes to play with dolls. We live in a small house. We are happy together." },
  { id:"a1-02", level:"A1", title:"My Morning", text:"I wake up at seven o'clock. I wash my face and brush my teeth. Then I eat breakfast. I usually eat bread and drink milk. After breakfast, I put on my clothes. I take my bag and go to school. The school is near my house. I walk there every day." },
  { id:"a1-03", level:"A1", title:"The Weather", text:"Today is a sunny day. The sky is blue. There are no clouds. It is warm outside. I like sunny days. I can play in the park. Tomorrow might be rainy. I do not like rain very much. But plants need water. So rain is good too." },
  { id:"a1-04", level:"A1", title:"My Favorite Food", text:"My favorite food is pizza. I like pizza with cheese and tomatoes. It tastes very good. I also like apples. They are sweet and healthy. I drink water every day. Sometimes I drink orange juice. I do not like coffee. It is too bitter for me." },
  { id:"a1-05", level:"A1", title:"At School", text:"I go to school five days a week. Monday is the first day. Friday is the last day. At school, I learn many things. I learn English and math. I also draw pictures. My teacher is nice. My classmates are friendly. We play together at break time." },
  { id:"a1-06", level:"A1", title:"My Pet", text:"I have a dog. His name is Max. He is brown and white. Max is very friendly. He likes to run in the garden. Every morning, I give him food and water. In the evening, we go for a walk. Max is my best friend. I love him very much." },
  { id:"a1-07", level:"A1", title:"Colors", text:"The world is full of colors. The sky is blue. The grass is green. The sun is yellow. Apples can be red or green. My favorite color is blue. It makes me feel calm. I have a blue shirt and blue shoes. What is your favorite color?" },
  { id:"a1-08", level:"A1", title:"Numbers", text:"I can count to twenty. One, two, three, four, five. Six, seven, eight, nine, ten. Eleven, twelve, thirteen, fourteen, fifteen. Sixteen, seventeen, eighteen, nineteen, twenty. I am ten years old. My brother is five years old. We like to count together." },
  { id:"a1-09", level:"A1", title:"The Park", text:"There is a park near my house. It is big and beautiful. Many people go there. Some people run. Some people walk their dogs. Children play on the swings. There are many trees and flowers. The air is fresh. I like to sit on a bench and read." },
  { id:"a1-10", level:"A1", title:"Shopping", text:"My mother and I go shopping on Saturday. We buy fruit and vegetables. We buy bread and milk. Sometimes we buy chocolate. The shop is small but nice. The shopkeeper smiles at us. We pay with cash. Then we carry the bags home." },
  { id:"a1-11", level:"A1", title:"My Room", text:"This is my room. It is not very big. There is a bed, a desk, and a chair. My books are on the desk. My clothes are in the wardrobe. There is a window. The window is open. The light comes in. I like my room. It is clean and quiet." },
  { id:"a1-12", level:"A1", title:"Days of the Week", text:"There are seven days in a week. They are Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday, and Sunday. I go to school from Monday to Friday. On Saturday, I play football. On Sunday, I rest at home with my family. Sunday is my favorite day." },
  { id:"a1-13", level:"A1", title:"My Hobby", text:"I like to draw pictures. It is my favorite hobby. I use colored pencils and paper. I draw animals and houses. Sometimes I draw my family. Drawing makes me happy. I want to be an artist when I grow up. Do you have a hobby?" },
  { id:"a1-14", level:"A1", title:"Transportation", text:"There are many ways to travel. Some people walk. Some people ride a bicycle. Some people take the bus. My father drives a car. I go to school on foot. Trains are fast. Planes are very fast. Boats travel on water. Each way is different." },
  { id:"a1-15", level:"A1", title:"Clothing", text:"I wear different clothes every day. On Monday, I wear a blue shirt. On Tuesday, I wear gray pants. I have a red jacket for cold days. In summer, I wear shorts and a T-shirt. My shoes are white. My socks are black. I like comfortable clothes." },
  { id:"a1-16", level:"A1", title:"The Body", text:"I have a head, two eyes, and one nose. I have two ears and one mouth. I use my eyes to see. I use my ears to hear. I use my mouth to eat and speak. I have two hands and ten fingers. I have two legs and two feet. The body is amazing." },
  { id:"a1-17", level:"A1", title:"My City", text:"I live in a small city. It is not very big. There are many shops and cafes. There is a big hospital and a school. People here are friendly. The streets are clean. There is a river near the city. I like to walk by the river. My city is peaceful." },
  { id:"a1-18", level:"A1", title:"Fruit", text:"I like to eat fruit. Bananas are yellow and sweet. Oranges are orange and juicy. Grapes are small and purple. Strawberries are red and delicious. Fruit is healthy. I eat an apple every day. An apple a day keeps the doctor away." },
  { id:"a1-19", level:"A1", title:"Drinks", text:"There are many drinks in the world. Water is the most important. Tea is warm and good in winter. Coffee is dark and strong. Milk is white and healthy. Juice is sweet and tasty. I drink water when I am thirsty. What do you like to drink?" },
  { id:"a1-20", level:"A1", title:"My Friend", text:"My best friend is Tom. He is eleven years old. He has short black hair. Tom likes football very much. We play together after school. He is funny and kind. He helps me with homework. I help him too. Good friends are important." },
  { id:"a1-21", level:"A1", title:"The Bedroom", text:"I sleep in my bedroom every night. There is a bed next to the window. There is a small lamp on the table. My teddy bear sits on the bed. The walls are white. The floor is wooden. At night, it is quiet. I close my eyes and dream." },
  { id:"a1-22", level:"A1", title:"Breakfast", text:"Breakfast is the first meal of the day. I eat breakfast at home. I usually eat cereal with milk. Sometimes I eat eggs and toast. I always drink a glass of water. Breakfast gives me energy. It helps me learn at school. Do not skip breakfast." },
  { id:"a1-23", level:"A1", title:"Sports", text:"I like sports very much. I play football on Saturday. I swim on Sunday. My brother plays basketball. My sister does gymnastics. Sports are good for the body. They make us strong and healthy. I want to learn tennis too. It looks fun." },
  { id:"a1-24", level:"A1", title:"Music", text:"I love music. I listen to music every day. I like pop music. It is happy and easy to sing. My mother likes classical music. My father likes rock music. We sometimes listen together. Music makes me feel good. I want to learn guitar." },
  { id:"a1-25", level:"A1", title:"Animals", text:"There are many animals in the world. Dogs and cats live with people. Lions and tigers live in the jungle. Fish live in water. Birds fly in the sky. Elephants are very big. Mice are very small. Every animal is special. We must protect them." },
  { id:"a1-26", level:"A1", title:"The Kitchen", text:"Our kitchen is small but nice. There is a fridge, a stove, and a sink. My mother cooks here every day. The fridge keeps food cold. The stove makes food hot. We eat at the kitchen table. After dinner, we wash the dishes. The kitchen is the heart of our home." },
  { id:"a1-27", level:"A1", title:"Time", text:"Time is important. I wake up at seven. School starts at eight. Lunch is at twelve. I go home at four. Dinner is at seven. I go to bed at nine. I have a clock in my room. It helps me know the time. We should not be late." },
  { id:"a1-28", level:"A1", title:"Jobs", text:"People have different jobs. Doctors help sick people. Teachers help students learn. Cooks make food. Drivers move people and things. Farmers grow food. Police keep us safe. Each job is important. What do you want to be?" },
  { id:"a1-29", level:"A1", title:"Feelings", text:"I have many feelings. When I get a gift, I feel happy. When I lose something, I feel sad. When there is a test, I feel nervous. When someone shouts, I feel scared. It is okay to have feelings. We should talk about them. Sharing helps us feel better." },
  { id:"a1-30", level:"A1", title:"Seasons", text:"There are four seasons. Spring is warm and green. Summer is hot and sunny. Autumn is cool and colorful. Winter is cold and white. I like spring because flowers bloom. Each season is beautiful. Nature changes but it is always wonderful." },

  // ==================== A2 ====================
  { id:"a2-01", level:"A2", title:"A Trip to the Zoo", text:"Last Sunday, my family and I went to the zoo. We saw many animals there. The elephants were very big and slow. The monkeys were funny and active. They jumped from tree to tree. We also saw a lion. He was sleeping under a tree. My sister liked the penguins. They walked in a funny way. We took many photos. At noon, we ate sandwiches near the lake. The weather was warm and sunny. It was a great day. I want to visit the zoo again soon." },
  { id:"a2-02", level:"A2", title:"My Weekend", text:"I usually have a busy weekend. On Saturday morning, I clean my room. In the afternoon, I meet my friends at the park. We play football or basketball. On Sunday, I visit my grandparents. My grandmother cooks a big lunch for us. After lunch, we watch television together. In the evening, I prepare my schoolbag for Monday. Sometimes I feel tired on Sunday night. But I enjoy my weekends very much. They help me relax after a long week." },
  { id:"a2-03", level:"A2", title:"Cooking Dinner", text:"Yesterday, I cooked dinner for my family. It was my first time. I made pasta with tomato sauce. First, I boiled water in a pot. Then I put the pasta in the water. I waited for ten minutes. Meanwhile, I cut tomatoes and onions. I fried them in a pan with oil. I added salt and pepper. When the pasta was ready, I mixed everything together. My parents said it was delicious. I was very proud. Cooking is not as hard as I thought." },
  { id:"a2-04", level:"A2", title:"A Letter to a Friend", text:"Dear Sarah, how are you? I hope you are well. I am writing to tell you about my new school. It is bigger than my old school. I have made three new friends. Their names are Lucy, Ben, and Emma. We sit together at lunch. My favorite subject is science. The teacher does fun experiments. I miss you very much. Please write back soon. Maybe you can visit me next month. I would love to show you around. Best wishes, Anna." },
  { id:"a2-05", level:"A2", title:"The Birthday Party", text:"Last month was my brother's tenth birthday. My parents organized a party for him. We invited ten of his friends. The party was in our garden. There were balloons and colorful lights. We played many games. The children danced and laughed. My mother made a big chocolate cake. It had ten candles on it. My brother blew out the candles and made a wish. Everyone sang happy birthday. Then we ate cake and ice cream. It was a wonderful party." },
  { id:"a2-06", level:"A2", title:"Learning English", text:"I started learning English two years ago. At first, it was difficult. The grammar was confusing and the pronunciation was hard. But I did not give up. I watched English movies with subtitles. I read simple books. I also used apps on my phone. Now I can understand basic conversations. I can write short emails too. My teacher says I have improved a lot. I still make mistakes, but that is okay. Learning a language takes time and practice." },
  { id:"a2-07", level:"A2", title:"A Rainy Day", text:"It was raining all day yesterday. I could not go outside. I stayed at home and read a book. It was a story about a brave knight. In the afternoon, I helped my mother bake cookies. The kitchen smelled wonderful. We listened to music while we worked. My brother played video games in his room. In the evening, the rain stopped. We opened the window. The air smelled fresh and clean. I like rainy days because they are peaceful." },
  { id:"a2-08", level:"A2", title:"My Neighbor", text:"My neighbor is an old woman named Mrs. Brown. She lives alone with her cat. She is very kind. Every morning, she waters the flowers in her garden. Sometimes she gives me fresh apples from her tree. Last week, she taught me how to knit. It was difficult at first, but she was patient. She told me stories about her youth. She traveled to many countries. I enjoy visiting her. She is like a grandmother to me." },
  { id:"a2-09", level:"A2", title:"Going to the Doctor", text:"I did not feel well last Tuesday. My throat hurt and I had a fever. My mother took me to the doctor. We waited in the waiting room for twenty minutes. The doctor was friendly. He checked my temperature and looked at my throat. He said I had a cold. He told me to drink warm water and rest. He also gave me some medicine. I stayed home for three days. Now I feel much better. I am glad my mother took me to see him." },
  { id:"a2-10", level:"A2", title:"The Library", text:"I go to the library every Saturday. It is a quiet place with many books. I usually borrow two or three books. The librarian knows my name. She recommends good books to me. Last week, I borrowed a mystery novel. It was exciting and hard to put down. The library also has computers. Students use them for homework. Sometimes there are story hours for children. The library is an important place in our town. Everyone should use it." },
  { id:"a2-11", level:"A2", title:"A New Phone", text:"My parents bought me a new phone for my birthday. It is not the most expensive one, but it works well. I use it to call my friends and send messages. I also take photos with it. The camera is quite good. I downloaded some useful apps. One app helps me learn English. Another app tracks my exercise. However, my parents told me not to use it too much. I should not stare at the screen before bed. I think that is good advice." },
  { id:"a2-12", level:"A2", title:"Exercise", text:"Exercise is very important for health. I try to exercise every day. In the morning, I do some stretching. After school, I run for twenty minutes. On weekends, I ride my bicycle in the park. Exercise makes me feel strong and happy. It also helps me sleep better at night. Some people say exercise is boring. But if you choose something fun, it is not. You can dance, swim, or play a sport. The important thing is to move your body." },
  { id:"a2-13", level:"A2", title:"Traveling by Train", text:"Last summer, I traveled to the mountains by train. The journey took four hours. I sat by the window and watched the scenery. We passed green fields, small villages, and a wide river. I read a book and listened to music. The train had a dining car. I ate a sandwich and drank tea there. The seats were comfortable. I talked to an old man who sat next to me. He told me about his travels in Europe. Traveling by train is relaxing. I prefer it to driving." },
  { id:"a2-14", level:"A2", title:"My Favorite Movie", text:"My favorite movie is about a young girl who wants to be a singer. She lives in a small village. Her family does not support her dream. But she works hard and never gives up. In the end, she becomes famous. The movie has beautiful music. It also teaches an important lesson. If you believe in yourself, you can achieve anything. I have watched this movie three times. Every time, it makes me cry and smile. I recommend it to everyone." },
  { id:"a2-15", level:"A2", title:"Gardening", text:"My grandfather loves gardening. He has a beautiful garden behind his house. He grows tomatoes, carrots, and lettuce. He also grows roses and sunflowers. Every morning, he wakes up early to water the plants. He removes weeds and checks for bugs. Last month, he taught me how to plant seeds. We dug small holes in the soil. We put the seeds inside and covered them. Now I have my own small plant. It is growing every day. Gardening is a peaceful hobby." },
  { id:"a2-16", level:"A2", title:"The Supermarket", text:"The supermarket is a big shop where you can buy many things. There are sections for fruit, vegetables, meat, and bread. There are also aisles for drinks, snacks, and cleaning products. I usually go with my mother. We make a list before we leave home. At the supermarket, we compare prices. Sometimes items are on sale. We use a shopping cart because we buy many things. At the checkout, we pay and pack the bags. It takes about one hour." },
  { id:"a2-17", level:"A2", title:"A Lost Dog", text:"Three days ago, I found a lost dog near my school. He was small and brown. He looked scared and hungry. I gave him some water from my bottle. Then I took him to the police station. The officers were kind. They checked if someone reported a missing dog. They took a photo and put it online. The next day, the owner came. She was very happy to see her dog. She thanked me with a big smile. I was glad I could help. Helping animals feels good." },
  { id:"a2-18", level:"A2", title:"Studying Abroad", text:"My cousin studied abroad last year. She went to a university in Canada. At first, she was nervous. Everything was new. The food was different. The weather was colder. But she met many friendly people. She lived in a dormitory with students from different countries. She learned about new cultures. Her English improved quickly. She traveled to beautiful places on weekends. Now she is back home. She says it was the best year of her life. She wants to work abroad one day." },
  { id:"a2-19", level:"A2", title:"Making Coffee", text:"My father taught me how to make coffee. First, you boil water in a kettle. Then you put coffee powder in a cup. Next, you pour the hot water slowly. You stir it with a spoon. You can add milk and sugar if you like. Some people drink black coffee. I prefer mine with a little milk. The smell of fresh coffee is wonderful. My father and I drink coffee together every Sunday morning. It is our special time. Making coffee is easy but you need good ingredients." },
  { id:"a2-20", level:"A2", title:"The Beach", text:"I went to the beach with my friends last weekend. The sand was golden and soft. The sea was blue and clear. We swam in the water for an hour. It was a little cold at first, but we got used to it. After swimming, we lay on our towels. The sun felt warm on our skin. We ate sandwiches and fruit for lunch. In the afternoon, we built a big sandcastle. We stayed until sunset. The sky turned orange and pink. It was a perfect day at the beach." },
  { id:"a2-21", level:"A2", title:"Moving House", text:"Last month, my family moved to a new house. The old house was too small. The new house has three bedrooms and a big garden. Moving was hard work. We packed our things into boxes. We labeled each box with a marker. My brother and I carried the small boxes. My father carried the heavy furniture. It took the whole day. In the evening, we ordered pizza because we were too tired to cook. Now I have my own room. I like the new house very much." },
  { id:"a2-22", level:"A2", title:"A Job Interview", text:"My sister had a job interview last week. She wants to work at a hotel. She was nervous the night before. She prepared by researching the company. She chose nice clothes to wear. She arrived ten minutes early. The manager asked her about her skills and experience. She spoke clearly and smiled. She asked questions about the job too. Two days later, they called her. She got the job! She was so happy. Preparation and confidence are important in an interview." },
  { id:"a2-23", level:"A2", title:"Winter Clothes", text:"Winter is coming soon. I need to prepare my warm clothes. I take out my thick coat from the wardrobe. I also find my scarf, gloves, and hat. My boots are near the door. I check if they still fit me. If they are too small, my mother buys new ones. I like my blue winter jacket. It keeps me warm in the snow. Layering clothes is important. You can remove a sweater if you get too hot. Winter fashion can be both warm and stylish." },
  { id:"a2-24", level:"A2", title:"Playing Chess", text:"My grandfather taught me to play chess. It is a game for two people. Each player has sixteen pieces. The goal is to checkmate the king. At first, I did not understand the rules. But my grandfather was patient. He explained each piece slowly. Now I can play basic games. Chess is not about luck. It is about thinking and planning. You must predict what your opponent will do. I play with my grandfather every Sunday. Sometimes I even win. It is a good way to exercise the brain." },
  { id:"a2-25", level:"A2", title:"The Internet", text:"The Internet has changed our lives. We use it every day. Students find information for homework. People send emails instead of letters. We can buy things online without leaving home. There are also videos and music. However, the Internet has problems. Some information is false. People spend too much time on social media. We must be careful online. Do not share personal details with strangers. The Internet is a powerful tool. We should use it wisely." },
  { id:"a2-26", level:"A2", title:"A Surprise Gift", text:"It was my mother's birthday last week. My father and I planned a surprise. We bought her a beautiful necklace. It was silver with a small heart. We also baked a cake. We hid everything in the kitchen. When my mother came home from work, we turned off the lights. We shouted happy birthday. She was very surprised. Her eyes were full of tears. She said it was the best birthday ever. Giving gifts to people we love is a wonderful feeling." },
  { id:"a2-27", level:"A2", title:"Camping", text:"Last summer, my friends and I went camping. We chose a spot near a lake. We put up two tents. It was harder than it looked. We collected wood and made a fire. We cooked sausages over the fire. They tasted delicious. At night, we told scary stories. We looked at the stars. There were so many. The next morning, we went swimming in the lake. The water was fresh and clean. Camping teaches you to live simply. I want to go again next year." },
  { id:"a2-28", level:"A2", title:"Healthy Food", text:"Eating healthy food is important. It gives your body energy. You should eat fruit and vegetables every day. They have vitamins. Whole grain bread is better than white bread. You should drink water instead of soda. Too much sugar is bad for your teeth. Fish and chicken are healthy meats. You do not need to stop eating sweets completely. Just eat them sometimes. A balanced diet helps you stay strong. Good food is the best medicine." },
  { id:"a2-29", level:"A2", title:"My Childhood", text:"When I was young, I lived in a small village. There were many fields and trees. I played outside every day with my friends. We climbed trees and caught insects. In summer, we swam in the river. There was a small school near my house. My teacher was very kind. She read stories to us every afternoon. I was shy but happy. I miss those simple days. Childhood is a special time. We should remember it with joy." },
  { id:"a2-30", level:"A2", title:"The Post Office", text:"I went to the post office yesterday. I needed to send a package to my aunt. The post office was busy. There was a line of people. I took a number and waited. When it was my turn, I gave the box to the clerk. She weighed it on a scale. Then she told me the price. I paid and she gave me a receipt. She said the package would arrive in three days. The post office also sells stamps and envelopes. It is an important place for sending things." },

  // ==================== B1 ====================
  { id:"b1-01", level:"B1", title:"Why I Love Reading", text:"Reading has been my favorite hobby since I was a child. Unlike watching television, reading allows me to use my imagination. When I read a novel, I can picture the characters and places in my mind. Books also teach me about different cultures and ideas. I usually read before bed because it helps me relax. My favorite genre is historical fiction. I enjoy learning about the past through stories. Some people say reading is boring, but I disagree. A good book can be as exciting as a movie. I try to read at least one book every month. Reading expands your mind and improves your vocabulary. It is a habit that everyone should develop." },
  { id:"b1-02", level:"B1", title:"Living in a Big City", text:"Living in a big city has both advantages and disadvantages. On the positive side, cities offer many job opportunities. You can find excellent schools, hospitals, and entertainment. Public transportation is usually convenient. However, city life also has problems. The cost of living is high. Traffic is terrible during rush hour. The noise and pollution can affect your health. Some people feel lonely even in a crowd. Personally, I enjoy the energy of the city. But I understand why others prefer the peace of the countryside. The best choice depends on your personality and lifestyle." },
  { id:"b1-03", level:"B1", title:"The Importance of Sleep", text:"Many people do not realize how important sleep is. Adults need about seven to eight hours per night. Teenagers need even more. When you do not sleep enough, your brain cannot work properly. You will have trouble concentrating at school or work. Lack of sleep also weakens your immune system. You might get sick more often. Unfortunately, modern life makes it hard to sleep well. People use phones late at night. The blue light from screens tricks your brain into staying awake. To sleep better, you should create a relaxing bedtime routine. Turn off devices an hour before bed. Read a book or listen to calm music instead. Good sleep is the foundation of good health." },
  { id:"b1-04", level:"B1", title:"Learning a New Language", text:"Learning a new language is one of the most rewarding skills you can develop. It opens doors to new cultures and friendships. When you speak another language, you can travel more easily. You can also understand foreign movies and music without subtitles. Many people think language learning is only for young people. This is not true. Adults can learn languages too. The key is consistency. You should practice a little every day rather than studying for hours once a week. Do not be afraid of making mistakes. Errors are part of the learning process. Technology has made language learning easier than ever. There are apps, podcasts, and online tutors available. With patience and effort, anyone can become bilingual." },
  { id:"b1-05", level:"B1", title:"Social Media and Friends", text:"Social media has changed the way we communicate with friends. In the past, people wrote letters or made phone calls. Now we send messages and share photos instantly. This is convenient, but it also creates problems. Online communication can feel shallow. We see perfect photos of other people's lives. This can make us feel jealous or inadequate. Some people have hundreds of online friends but feel lonely in real life. I believe social media is a useful tool, but it should not replace face-to-face meetings. Real friendships require time and attention. We should put down our phones and talk to the people around us. Balance is the key to healthy relationships in the digital age." },
  { id:"b1-06", level:"B1", title:"A Memorable Journey", text:"Two years ago, I took a train across my country. The trip lasted three days. I traveled alone for the first time. I was nervous but excited. On the first day, I met an elderly couple in the dining car. They told me stories about their travels in Africa. On the second day, the landscape changed dramatically. We passed through mountains, forests, and deserts. I read books and wrote in my journal. On the third day, I arrived at the ocean. The sunset was the most beautiful thing I had ever seen. That journey taught me that travel is not just about the destination. It is about the people you meet and the things you see along the way." },
  { id:"b1-07", level:"B1", title:"Working from Home", text:"Working from home has become very common. Many companies now allow employees to work remotely. There are clear benefits. You save time because you do not need to commute. You can wear comfortable clothes. Some people are more productive at home. However, remote work also has challenges. It can be difficult to separate work life from personal life. You might feel isolated without colleagues around. Communication with your team requires more effort. Video meetings are not the same as real conversations. In my opinion, a mix of office and home work is ideal. It gives you flexibility while maintaining social connections. The future of work will probably be hybrid." },
  { id:"b1-08", level:"B1", title:"Environmental Problems", text:"Our planet faces many environmental problems. Climate change is the most serious. Temperatures are rising. Ice at the poles is melting. Sea levels are going up. Many animals are losing their homes. Another major issue is plastic pollution. Millions of tons of plastic end up in the ocean every year. Fish and birds eat small pieces of plastic. This harms their health. Deforestation is also a concern. We cut down forests for farms and buildings. Trees absorb carbon dioxide. Without them, the air quality gets worse. Solving these problems requires action from governments, companies, and individuals. We should use less plastic. We should recycle more. We should also support clean energy like wind and solar power." },
  { id:"b1-09", level:"B1", title:"My Favorite Teacher", text:"My favorite teacher was Mr. Henderson. He taught me history in high school. He was different from other teachers. He did not just read from the textbook. He told stories as if we were watching a movie. He made ancient civilizations come alive. He also cared about his students. When I was struggling with my grades, he stayed after class to help me. He believed in me when I did not believe in myself. Because of him, I developed a love for history. I even decided to study it at university. A great teacher does more than share knowledge. They inspire you to learn and grow. I will always remember Mr. Henderson." },
  { id:"b1-10", level:"B1", title:"The History of Pizza", text:"Pizza is one of the most popular foods in the world. But it has a long history. Flatbreads with toppings existed in ancient Egypt and Rome. However, modern pizza began in Naples, Italy. In the eighteenth century, poor people in Naples ate flatbread with tomatoes. In 1889, a baker created a pizza for Queen Margherita. He used tomato, mozzarella, and basil. These colors matched the Italian flag. This became the famous Margherita pizza. Italian immigrants brought pizza to America. The first pizzeria opened in New York in 1905. Today, pizza exists in many styles. But the best pizza is still found in Naples. It is even protected by UNESCO as cultural heritage." },
  { id:"b1-11", level:"B1", title:"How to Save Money", text:"Saving money is an important skill. Many people spend everything they earn. Then they have no money for emergencies. To save money, you should first track your spending. Write down everything you buy for one month. You will see where your money goes. Next, create a budget. Decide how much you need for rent, food, and transport. Then set aside some money for savings. Even small amounts help. You should also avoid impulse buying. When you want something, wait three days. If you still want it, then buy it. Finally, compare prices before shopping. There are apps that show you the best deals. Saving money gives you freedom and security." },
  { id:"b1-12", level:"B1", title:"The Benefits of Walking", text:"Walking is the simplest form of exercise. You do not need special equipment. You do not need a gym membership. You just need a pair of comfortable shoes. Walking has many health benefits. It strengthens your heart and muscles. It helps control your weight. It also improves your mood. When you walk outside, you get fresh air and sunlight. This reduces stress and anxiety. I walk for thirty minutes every morning. I listen to podcasts or music. Sometimes I walk with a friend. We talk and enjoy the scenery. In cities, walking is often faster than driving short distances. It is also better for the environment. If you want to be healthier, start walking today." },
  { id:"b1-13", level:"B1", title:"A Difficult Decision", text:"Last year, I had to make a difficult decision. I received two job offers at the same time. One was in my hometown. The salary was average, but I could live with my family. The other was in a big city. The salary was higher, but the cost of living was also higher. I would have to live alone. I spent two weeks thinking about it. I made lists of pros and cons. I talked to my parents and friends. In the end, I chose the city job. It was scary to move away. But I knew it was the right choice for my career. Difficult decisions are never easy. But if you think carefully, you will find the answer." },
  { id:"b1-14", level:"B1", title:"Technology in Schools", text:"Technology is changing education. Many schools now use tablets and computers. Students can access information instantly. They can watch educational videos. They can collaborate on projects online. This makes learning more engaging. However, there are concerns. Some students get distracted by games and social media. Not all families can afford devices. There is also a question about screen time. Young children should not stare at screens all day. Teachers need training to use technology effectively. In my view, technology is a useful tool, but it cannot replace good teaching. The best classrooms combine traditional methods with modern tools. Education is about human connection, not just information." },
  { id:"b1-15", level:"B1", title:"Cultural Differences", text:"When I traveled to Japan, I noticed many cultural differences. People bow instead of shaking hands. They take off their shoes before entering a house. The food was very different from mine. I tried sushi and noodles. At first, I missed my usual food. But after a week, I started to enjoy the new flavors. I also noticed that people were very polite. They did not talk loudly on trains. They queued patiently for everything. These differences surprised me at first. But then I realized that every culture has its own beauty. Traveling teaches you to be open-minded. You learn that there is no single right way to live." },
  { id:"b1-16", level:"B1", title:"Starting a Business", text:"My uncle started his own bakery five years ago. It was not easy. He had to find money to rent a shop. He had to buy ovens and mixers. He worked twelve hours a day. At first, not many customers came. But he did not give up. He used social media to advertise. He offered free samples in the park. Slowly, people started to notice his delicious bread. Now his bakery is famous in the neighborhood. He employs three people. He says starting a business requires courage and patience. You will face problems. But if you believe in your product, you can succeed. His story inspires me to follow my own dreams one day." },
  { id:"b1-17", level:"B1", title:"The Power of Music", text:"Music has a unique power over human emotions. A sad song can make us cry. An energetic song can make us dance. Scientists have studied the effects of music on the brain. They found that music activates many areas at once. It can improve memory in elderly people. It can reduce pain in patients. Music also brings people together. At concerts, strangers sing the same words. They feel connected. Different cultures use music for different purposes. Some use it for religious ceremonies. Others use it for celebrations. I play guitar to relax after a stressful day. Music does not need translation. It speaks directly to the heart. That is its true magic." },
  { id:"b1-18", level:"B1", title:"Public Transportation", text:"Public transportation is essential in modern cities. Buses, trains, and subways move millions of people every day. Using public transport has many advantages. It reduces traffic jams. It lowers air pollution. It is cheaper than owning a car. You can read or work while traveling. However, public transport also has problems. During rush hour, trains are crowded. Buses can be late. Some areas do not have good connections. In my city, the government is investing in new metro lines. They want to make travel faster and cleaner. I believe good public transport makes a city more livable. We should use it whenever possible. It benefits both the individual and the community." },
  { id:"b1-19", level:"B1", title:"Stress and Health", text:"Stress is a normal part of life. A little stress can motivate us. But too much stress is dangerous. It can cause headaches, stomach problems, and trouble sleeping. Chronic stress weakens the immune system. Many people feel stressed because of work pressure. Others feel stressed because of personal problems. It is important to recognize the signs of stress. When you feel overwhelmed, take a break. Exercise is an excellent way to reduce stress. Talking to a friend also helps. Some people practice meditation or deep breathing. Finding a healthy balance between work and rest is crucial. Your mental health is just as important as your physical health." },
  { id:"b1-20", level:"B1", title:"Volunteering", text:"Last summer, I volunteered at an animal shelter. I worked there for one month. My tasks included feeding the animals and cleaning their spaces. It was hard work. Sometimes it smelled bad. But it was also very rewarding. The animals needed love and care. When a dog wagged its tail at me, I felt happy inside. Volunteering taught me many things. I learned responsibility. I learned to appreciate simple comforts. I also met kind people who shared my values. They became my friends. You do not need money to help others. You just need time and compassion. Everyone should try volunteering at least once. It changes your perspective on life." },
  { id:"b1-21", level:"B1", title:"Online Shopping", text:"Online shopping has become extremely popular. You can buy almost anything on the Internet. Clothes, electronics, food, and furniture are all available. The main advantage is convenience. You can shop at any time. You do not need to leave your house. You can compare prices easily. However, online shopping has risks. Sometimes the product looks different from the photo. Returns can be complicated. There is also a security risk. Hackers might steal your credit card information. In addition, some people buy things they do not need. The ease of clicking a button encourages impulse buying. I shop online sometimes, but I prefer to see expensive items in person first. Wise consumers know how to shop safely." },
  { id:"b1-22", level:"B1", title:"A Book That Changed Me", text:"When I was sixteen, I read a book called Man's Search for Meaning. It was written by Viktor Frankl. He was a psychologist who survived a concentration camp. The book describes his experiences and his ideas about life. Frankl believed that humans can find meaning even in suffering. This idea shocked me. I had always thought happiness was the goal. But Frankl said meaning is more important. After reading the book, I changed my attitude toward difficulties. I stopped complaining about small problems. I started asking what I could learn from challenges. That book did not just entertain me. It transformed the way I see the world. Some books stay with you forever." },
  { id:"b1-23", level:"B1", title:"The Future of Work", text:"The world of work is changing rapidly. Automation and artificial intelligence are replacing some jobs. Factories now use robots. Banks use software to analyze data. This worries many people. Will machines take all our jobs? Experts say the answer is complex. Some jobs will disappear. But new jobs will appear. Someone needs to build and maintain the robots. Someone needs to program the software. The key is to develop skills that machines cannot easily copy. Creativity, empathy, and critical thinking are valuable. Workers will also change careers more often. Learning will not stop after school. It will continue throughout life. The future belongs to those who can adapt." },
  { id:"b1-24", level:"B1", title:"Healthy Eating Habits", text:"What we eat affects how we feel. A healthy diet includes variety. You should eat vegetables, fruits, grains, and proteins. Processed food is convenient but unhealthy. It often contains too much salt, sugar, and fat. Fast food is tasty, but eating it regularly leads to health problems. Many young people skip breakfast. This is a mistake. Breakfast gives you energy for the day. It is also important to drink enough water. Sometimes we think we are hungry when we are actually thirsty. Another good habit is eating slowly. When you eat fast, your body does not have time to feel full. Small changes in diet can have big effects on health." },
  { id:"b1-25", level:"B1", title:"Learning from Mistakes", text:"Everyone makes mistakes. What matters is how we respond to them. Some people feel ashamed and hide their errors. This prevents growth. Successful people see mistakes as lessons. Thomas Edison failed thousands of times before inventing the light bulb. He said he did not fail. He just found ways that did not work. This attitude is powerful. When I fail a test, I now analyze what went wrong. Did I study enough? Did I understand the material? This helps me improve. Fear of failure stops many people from trying new things. But if you never try, you never learn. Mistakes are proof that you are pushing your limits." },
  { id:"b1-26", level:"B1", title:"Modern Art", text:"Modern art can be confusing. A painting might look like random colors. A sculpture might look like a pile of metal. Many people say, my child could do that. But modern art is about ideas, not just skill. Artists want to make us think differently. They challenge traditional beauty. They express emotions that cannot be put into words. I visited a modern art museum last month. At first, I did not understand much. Then I read the descriptions next to each piece. I learned about the artists' intentions. Some works were about war. Others were about identity. By the end, I appreciated the creativity. Art does not always need to be beautiful. Sometimes it needs to be thought-provoking." },
  { id:"b1-27", level:"B1", title:"Traveling Solo", text:"Last year, I traveled alone for the first time. I went to Portugal for one week. Before the trip, I was nervous. What if I got lost? What if I felt lonely? But once I arrived, those fears disappeared. Traveling alone gives you complete freedom. You decide where to go. You decide when to eat. You meet more people because you are not in a group. I talked to locals in cafes. I joined a walking tour and made friends. Of course, I had to be careful. I kept my money in different places. I told my family my plans every day. Solo travel taught me to trust myself. It was the most liberating experience of my life." },
  { id:"b1-28", level:"B1", title:"Renewable Energy", text:"The world needs to move away from fossil fuels. Coal, oil, and gas create pollution. They also cause climate change. Renewable energy offers a solution. Solar power uses energy from the sun. Wind power uses energy from the wind. Both are clean and unlimited. Many countries are building solar farms and wind turbines. The technology is improving quickly. Solar panels are now cheaper than before. However, renewable energy has challenges. The sun does not shine at night. The wind does not always blow. We need better batteries to store energy. We also need to update old power systems. Despite these challenges, the future is clear. Renewable energy is the path to a cleaner planet." },
  { id:"b1-29", level:"B1", title:"The Role of Family", text:"Family means different things to different people. For some, it is parents and siblings. For others, it is close friends. In many cultures, extended family is very important. Grandparents, aunts, and uncles live together or nearby. In modern Western society, families are often smaller and more separate. Young people move away for work. They visit only on holidays. Technology helps us stay connected. We can video call relatives across the world. But digital connection is not the same as being together. Family provides emotional support. They celebrate our successes. They comfort us in hard times. No matter how society changes, family remains a foundation of human life." },
  { id:"b1-30", level:"B1", title:"Digital Detox", text:"Last month, I tried a digital detox. I did not use my phone or computer for forty-eight hours. The first few hours were strange. I kept reaching for my phone. But after a while, I felt calmer. Without notifications, my mind was quieter. I had time to read, cook, and take long walks. I noticed things I usually ignore. The color of the sky. The sound of birds. I also talked more with my family. We played board games. By the end, I realized how much time I waste online. I decided to set limits. Now I turn off my phone at nine every night. A digital detox does not need to be long. Even one day can refresh your mind." },

  // ==================== B2 ====================
  { id:"b2-01", level:"B2", title:"The Impact of Artificial Intelligence", text:"Artificial intelligence is transforming nearly every aspect of modern life. In healthcare, algorithms can detect diseases from medical images with remarkable accuracy. In transportation, self-driving cars promise to reduce accidents caused by human error. In education, adaptive learning systems personalize content for individual students. Yet these advances raise profound questions. What happens to workers whose jobs are automated? How do we ensure algorithms do not inherit human biases? There are also ethical concerns about privacy. AI systems require vast amounts of data. Who controls that data? Who profits from it? Some experts warn about artificial general intelligence, a hypothetical future where machines surpass human intellect. They argue we need safety measures now. Others believe such fears are exaggerated. They point out that current AI is narrow, capable only of specific tasks. What is clear is that AI regulation cannot keep pace with innovation. Governments struggle to understand the technology, let alone govern it effectively. Society must engage in an honest conversation about the kind of future we want to build. The decisions we make today will shape the relationship between humans and machines for generations." },
  { id:"b2-02", level:"B2", title:"Should University Education Be Free?", text:"The question of whether university education should be free has sparked intense debate worldwide. Proponents argue that education is a fundamental right, not a privilege. They point to countries like Germany and Norway, where public universities charge no tuition. In these nations, higher education is accessible to talented students regardless of family income. This leads to greater social mobility and a more skilled workforce. Critics, however, raise practical concerns. Universities require enormous funding. Professors need salaries. Laboratories need equipment. If students do not pay, taxpayers must cover the cost. Some argue this is unfair to those who never attend university. Others worry that free education would lower quality. When universities depend entirely on state funding, they may face political pressure. There is also the question of incentives. If education is free, some students might not take it seriously. They have no financial stake in their success. A middle path exists in many countries. Students pay reduced fees, and the government provides loans that are repaid based on future income. This balances accessibility with sustainability. Ultimately, the best system depends on a country's economic situation and cultural values." },
  { id:"b2-03", level:"B2", title:"The Decline of Traditional Media", text:"For decades, newspapers and television networks were the gatekeepers of information. They decided what the public needed to know. Journalists followed ethical codes. Editors checked facts before publication. This system was not perfect, but it provided a degree of reliability. Today, the landscape has shifted dramatically. Social media platforms now dominate news distribution. Anyone can publish content instantly. While this democratizes information, it also creates problems. False stories spread faster than corrections. Algorithms prioritize engagement over accuracy. Sensational headlines generate clicks. Thoughtful analysis does not. As a result, traditional media outlets are struggling financially. Advertising revenue has moved to tech giants. Many newspapers have closed. Others have reduced their staff. Investigative journalism, which is expensive and time-consuming, is particularly threatened. Some argue that quality journalism should be supported by public funding or subscriptions. Others hope that new business models will emerge. What is certain is that an informed citizenry requires reliable sources. The challenge for modern society is to preserve the best aspects of traditional journalism while adapting to the digital age." },
  { id:"b2-04", level:"B2", title:"Immigration and Cultural Identity", text:"Immigration has always been a powerful force shaping societies. Throughout history, people have moved in search of safety, opportunity, or adventure. When immigrants arrive, they bring their languages, traditions, and perspectives. This enriches the host country. Cities like London and New York are vibrant precisely because of their diversity. However, immigration also creates tensions. Some native-born citizens feel their culture is threatened. They worry about competition for jobs and housing. Language barriers can lead to social fragmentation. Politicians often exploit these fears for electoral gain. The debate usually frames the issue as a choice between open borders and strict control. Reality is more nuanced. Most economists agree that immigration has a net positive effect on the economy. Immigrants fill labor shortages. They start businesses. They contribute more in taxes than they receive in benefits over time. The real challenge is integration. How do we help newcomers participate fully in society while respecting their heritage? Successful integration requires investment in language education, employment support, and anti-discrimination policies. It also requires a shift in attitude. A society that sees diversity as a strength will thrive more than one that sees it as a threat." },
  { id:"b2-05", level:"B2", title:"The Psychology of Procrastination", text:"Procrastination is often misunderstood as simple laziness. In reality, it is a complex psychological behavior rooted in emotion regulation. When people procrastinate, they are not avoiding the task itself. They are avoiding the negative emotions associated with it. Fear of failure, perfectionism, and boredom can all trigger procrastination. The immediate relief of avoiding the task reinforces the behavior. This creates a vicious cycle. The task becomes more stressful as the deadline approaches. The procrastinator feels guilty and anxious. Ironically, many procrastinators are highly ambitious. Their high standards make starting intimidating. Research suggests several strategies to overcome procrastination. Breaking tasks into smaller steps reduces the emotional barrier. The two-minute rule suggests that if a task takes less than two minutes, do it immediately. Self-compassion also helps. People who forgive themselves for past procrastination are less likely to repeat it. Understanding that procrastination is about mood management, not time management, is the first step toward change." },
  { id:"b2-06", level:"B2", title:"Sustainable Fashion", text:"The fashion industry is one of the most polluting industries on Earth. It produces more carbon emissions than international flights and shipping combined. Much of this comes from fast fashion, where clothes are designed to be worn a few times and discarded. The environmental cost is staggering. Cotton farming uses enormous amounts of water. Synthetic fabrics release microplastics into oceans. Dyeing fabrics pollutes rivers in developing countries. The human cost is equally troubling. Many garment workers earn poverty wages in unsafe conditions. Sustainable fashion offers an alternative. It emphasizes quality over quantity. It uses organic or recycled materials. It ensures fair wages for workers. Some brands have adopted circular models, where old clothes are collected and remade into new items. Consumers also have a role to play. Buying less, choosing well, and caring for clothes extends their lifespan. Second-hand shopping has become fashionable among young people. Thrift stores and online resale platforms are growing rapidly. Sustainable fashion is not about sacrificing style. It is about aligning our choices with our values." },
  { id:"b2-07", level:"B2", title:"The Gig Economy", text:"The gig economy refers to a labor market where temporary positions are common. Workers are paid per task rather than receiving a regular salary. Platforms like Uber, Deliveroo, and Fiverr have made this model mainstream. Supporters praise the flexibility. Workers can choose when and how much they work. This suits students, parents, and those seeking supplemental income. Critics highlight the downsides. Gig workers are usually classified as independent contractors. This means they lack basic protections. They receive no health insurance, no paid leave, and no job security. Their income is unpredictable. If they get sick, they cannot work and they do not earn. Some governments have begun to challenge this classification. Courts in several countries have ruled that gig workers should be treated as employees. The companies argue that flexibility would be lost if they had to follow traditional employment laws. The gig economy is not going away. But the legal framework surrounding it is still evolving. Society must decide what protections workers deserve in this new landscape." },
  { id:"b2-08", level:"B2", title:"Space Exploration: Costs and Benefits", text:"Space exploration has always captured human imagination. From the moon landing to Mars rovers, these achievements represent the pinnacle of scientific endeavor. Supporters argue that space research drives innovation. Technologies developed for space often find applications on Earth. Satellite systems enable global communication and weather prediction. Understanding other planets helps us protect our own. However, space exploration is extraordinarily expensive. A single Mars mission can cost billions of dollars. Critics ask whether this money could be better spent on earthly problems. Poverty, disease, and climate change remain urgent challenges. Does it make sense to search for life on Mars while people starve here? Proponents respond that the budget for space is tiny compared to military spending. They also argue that scientific progress is not a zero-sum game. Investment in space inspires young people to study science. It fosters international cooperation. The International Space Station involves multiple nations working together peacefully. Perhaps the real question is not whether to explore space, but how to do it responsibly and inclusively." },
  { id:"b2-09", level:"B2", title:"Genetically Modified Food", text:"Genetically modified organisms, or GMOs, are perhaps the most controversial topic in modern agriculture. Scientists alter the DNA of crops to make them resistant to pests, diseases, and herbicides. This can increase yields and reduce the need for chemical sprays. In a world with a growing population, such efficiency is appealing. Yet opponents raise serious concerns. They worry about long-term health effects. Although most scientific bodies say GMOs are safe to eat, some consumers remain skeptical. There are also environmental risks. Modified genes might spread to wild plants, creating superweeds. The corporate control of seeds is another issue. A few large companies dominate the GMO seed market. Farmers must buy new seeds each year instead of saving their own. This increases their costs and dependence. In many European countries, GMO crops are heavily restricted. In contrast, the Americas have widely adopted them. The debate reflects deeper tensions between scientific progress, corporate power, and public trust. Finding common ground requires transparent research and clear labeling. Consumers deserve to know what they are eating." },
  { id:"b2-10", level:"B2", title:"The Power of Habit", text:"Habits shape our lives more than we realize. Researchers estimate that forty percent of daily actions are habitual rather than conscious decisions. Understanding how habits work can help us change them. According to behavioral scientists, every habit consists of three parts. First is the cue, a trigger that tells your brain to start the behavior. Second is the routine, the behavior itself. Third is the reward, which reinforces the loop. To change a habit, you must identify these components. Some people try to eliminate bad habits through willpower alone. This usually fails because willpower is a limited resource. A more effective approach is to replace the routine while keeping the same cue and reward. For example, if stress triggers you to eat junk food, you might replace eating with a short walk. The cue and reward remain, but the behavior changes. Small habits compound over time. Reading ten pages a day seems minor. But in a year, that is over fifteen books. Conversely, small negative habits can accumulate into serious problems. The key is to design your environment so that good habits become the path of least resistance." },
  { id:"b2-11", level:"B2", title:"Remote Work and Urban Decline", text:"The shift to remote work during the pandemic had unexpected consequences for cities. Downtown offices emptied. Restaurants and shops that served office workers lost customers. Commercial real estate values dropped. Some predicted the death of the city. Yet cities have survived previous disruptions. They adapted after the suburban boom of the mid-twentieth century. They will likely adapt again. What is changing is the nature of urban space. There is growing demand for mixed-use neighborhoods where people can live, work, and play without long commutes. Empty office buildings are being converted into apartments. City centers might become more residential and less commercial. Remote work has also affected where people choose to live. Many have moved to smaller towns with lower costs of living. This has caused housing prices to rise in previously affordable areas. The long-term impact on urban geography is still unfolding. What seems clear is that the rigid separation of work and home is dissolving. The future city will need to be more flexible, more green, and more human-centered." },
  { id:"b2-12", level:"B2", title:"Climate Change and Individual Responsibility", text:"Climate change is the defining challenge of our era. The science is unequivocal. Human activities, particularly burning fossil fuels, are warming the planet. The consequences include extreme weather, rising seas, and biodiversity loss. Addressing this crisis requires action at every level. Governments must implement policies. Corporations must transform their practices. But what about individuals? Some argue that personal choices are irrelevant. They say the real culprits are large corporations and wealthy nations. Individual actions like using paper straws are meaningless distractions. There is truth to this. A hundred companies are responsible for seventy percent of emissions. Systemic change matters more than personal virtue. However, this argument can become an excuse for inaction. Individual choices do add up. They also send signals to markets and politicians. When millions of people demand plant-based food, companies respond. When voters prioritize climate, governments act. The most effective approach combines systemic advocacy with personal responsibility. We need both top-down policy and bottom-up cultural change." },
  { id:"b2-13", level:"B2", title:"The Ethics of Animal Testing", text:"For centuries, scientists have used animals to test medicines and cosmetics. This practice has saved countless human lives. Vaccines, antibiotics, and cancer treatments were all developed with animal research. Yet the moral cost is significant. Animals in laboratories often suffer pain, confinement, and psychological distress. Ethical frameworks differ on how to balance human benefit against animal suffering. Utilitarians might argue that the reduction of human suffering justifies the means. Rights-based theorists reject this calculus. They argue that sentient beings have inherent worth that cannot be overridden by utility. Technological advances are offering alternatives. Organ-on-a-chip technology simulates human organs. Computer models can predict drug reactions. These methods are not yet advanced enough to replace all animal testing. But they are improving. Many countries have banned cosmetic testing on animals. The scientific community is increasingly committed to the three Rs. Replace animal use where possible. Reduce the number of animals used. Refine procedures to minimize suffering. The goal is a future where scientific progress and compassion coexist." },
  { id:"b2-14", level:"B2", title:"Social Media and Mental Health", text:"The relationship between social media and mental health is complicated. These platforms connect us with friends and information. They allow marginalized voices to be heard. Yet research increasingly links heavy social media use to anxiety, depression, and poor body image. Several mechanisms may explain this. Curated perfection dominates feeds. Users compare their ordinary lives to others' highlight reels. This breeds inadequacy. The constant stream of notifications fragments attention. Deep focus becomes difficult. Sleep suffers when people scroll late into the night. Cyberbullying adds another dimension of harm. Young people are particularly vulnerable. Their identities are still forming. The dopamine-driven design of these platforms exploits psychological vulnerabilities. The business model depends on maximizing engagement. Controversial content generates more clicks than calm discourse. Some propose regulation. Others advocate digital literacy education. Individuals can also take control. Setting time limits, curating feeds, and taking breaks can help. The challenge is to enjoy the benefits of connection without surrendering our well-being to algorithms designed to addict us." },
  { id:"b2-15", level:"B2", title:"Universal Basic Income", text:"Universal basic income is the idea of giving every citizen regular cash payments with no strings attached. Advocates argue it would reduce poverty and bureaucracy. It would provide a safety net as automation eliminates jobs. It would give people freedom to pursue education, art, or care work without financial desperation. Experiments in Finland and Kenya have shown promising results. Recipients reported lower stress and better mental health. Some started small businesses. Critics raise objections. They worry about the cost. Providing basic income to everyone, including the wealthy, would require massive taxation. They argue it would reduce the incentive to work. Society might lose productivity. There are also political concerns. Once established, basic income would be difficult to reduce. Supporters counter that existing welfare systems are already expensive and inefficient. Basic income would eliminate complex administrative costs. The debate reflects deeper questions about the purpose of work and the meaning of citizenship in an automated age. As job markets transform, these questions will only become more urgent." },
  { id:"b2-16", level:"B2", title:"The Future of Privacy", text:"Privacy is under unprecedented threat. Surveillance cameras cover our streets. Smartphones track our locations. Search engines record our questions. Social media knows our preferences better than our families do. This data is not merely collected. It is analyzed, sold, and used to influence behavior. Governments justify surveillance as necessary for security. Companies justify data collection as necessary for personalized services. The public often accepts these trade-offs without understanding the consequences. What happens when data falls into the wrong hands? What happens when authoritarian regimes use technology to monitor dissidents? The concept of privacy is evolving. Younger generations often share willingly. They value connection over concealment. Yet privacy is not just about hiding secrets. It is about autonomy. It is the right to define your own identity rather than having it defined by data points. Legal frameworks like GDPR in Europe represent progress. But technology moves faster than legislation. Protecting privacy in the digital age requires both legal safeguards and personal vigilance." },
  { id:"b2-17", level:"B2", title:"Tourism and Its Dark Side", text:"Tourism is one of the world's largest industries. It creates jobs and generates wealth. It promotes cultural exchange. Yet mass tourism has devastating consequences. Popular destinations suffer from overcrowding. Historic cities become theme parks. Local residents are priced out of their own neighborhoods. Environmental damage is severe. Cruise ships pollute the water. Hikers destroy fragile ecosystems. Wildlife is disturbed for selfie opportunities. The carbon footprint of international travel contributes to climate change. Some cities have begun to fight back. Amsterdam has restricted vacation rentals. Venice charges entry fees on busy days. Bhutan limits tourist numbers and charges high daily fees. The concept of sustainable tourism is gaining traction. Travelers are encouraged to visit lesser-known places. They should respect local customs. They should minimize waste and carbon emissions. The question is whether the industry can transform itself before it destroys the very attractions it sells. Conscious travel is not just a trend. It is a necessity." },
  { id:"b2-18", level:"B2", title:"The Science of Happiness", text:"Happiness has become a subject of serious scientific study. Positive psychology, founded in the late twentieth century, examines what makes life worth living. Researchers have identified several factors that correlate with well-being. Strong social relationships are the strongest predictor. People with close friends and family report higher life satisfaction. Meaningful work also matters. Not necessarily high-paying work, but work that feels purposeful. Physical health and regular exercise contribute significantly. Interestingly, income matters only up to a point. Once basic needs are met, additional money has diminishing returns on happiness. Genetics play a role too. Some people have a naturally higher baseline mood. But circumstances and choices account for a substantial portion. Gratitude practices, meditation, and acts of kindness have measurable effects on brain chemistry. The pursuit of happiness is not selfish. Happy people are more creative, more productive, and more altruistic. Understanding the science allows us to make better choices about how to spend our limited time." },
  { id:"b2-19", level:"B2", title:"Automation and Employment", text:"The relationship between technology and employment has always been complex. The Industrial Revolution destroyed some crafts but created factory jobs. The computer age eliminated typists but created software engineers. Today, artificial intelligence threatens to disrupt even highly skilled professions. Lawyers use algorithms to review documents. Doctors use AI to diagnose diseases. Accountants rely on automated systems. The difference this time may be speed and scale. Previous technological transitions took generations. This one is happening in years. Workers may not have time to retrain. Economists debate whether new jobs will emerge as old ones vanish. History suggests they will. But the transition period could be painful. Governments need to prepare. Education systems should focus on skills that machines struggle with. Creativity, emotional intelligence, and complex problem-solving are harder to automate. Social safety nets may need expansion. Universal basic income, though controversial, is being discussed seriously. The goal should not be to stop progress. It should be to ensure that the benefits of automation are shared broadly rather than concentrating among the wealthy." },
  { id:"b2-20", level:"B2", title:"Multilingualism and Brain Health", text:"Speaking multiple languages is not just a practical skill. It is also a workout for the brain. Neuroscientists have found that bilingualism enhances cognitive flexibility. Multilingual individuals are better at switching between tasks. They often show greater creativity in problem-solving. Most remarkably, bilingualism appears to delay the onset of dementia by several years. The brain of a bilingual person develops denser gray matter in regions associated with executive function. Constantly managing two languages strengthens these neural pathways. Some worry that raising children bilingual will confuse them. Research shows the opposite. Children naturally separate languages. They may mix them occasionally, but this is normal and temporary. The benefits extend beyond cognition. Multilingual individuals often demonstrate greater cultural empathy. They understand that concepts do not map neatly across languages. This awareness fosters open-mindedness. In a globalized world, multilingualism is an asset. Encouraging language learning in schools is one of the smartest investments a society can make." },
  { id:"b2-21", level:"B2", title:"The Right to Disconnect", text:"Digital technology has dissolved the boundary between work and personal life. Emails arrive at midnight. Colleagues message during vacations. The expectation of constant availability creates chronic stress. In response, several countries have introduced the right to disconnect. France was the first major nation to legislate this right in 2017. Employers cannot punish workers for ignoring work communications outside hours. Other European nations have followed. The idea is gaining traction globally. Supporters argue that rest is essential for productivity and mental health. Workers cannot perform well if they never truly stop working. Critics worry about practical enforcement. In global companies, time zones complicate matters. Some industries require emergency responsiveness. Others argue that rigid rules reduce flexibility. Workers who prefer irregular hours might be constrained. The debate reflects a deeper tension. Technology promised to liberate us from the office. Instead, it has colonized our homes and minds. Establishing boundaries is not anti-progress. It is a necessary adaptation to a connected world." },
  { id:"b2-22", level:"B2", title:"Fast Fashion and Pollution", text:"Fast fashion has democratized style. Anyone can buy trendy clothes at low prices. But the environmental cost is staggering. The fashion industry produces ten percent of global carbon emissions. It consumes more water than any industry except agriculture. Synthetic fabrics shed microplastics into waterways. Textile dyeing pollutes rivers in manufacturing hubs. The human cost is equally severe. Workers in developing nations often labor in unsafe conditions for poverty wages. The fast fashion model depends on rapid turnover. Clothes are designed to fall apart after a few washes. Consumers buy more and discard more. The average garment is worn only seven times before disposal. Landfills are overflowing with textiles. Some brands have made commitments to sustainability. They use organic cotton and recycled polyester. But critics call this greenwashing. Real change requires systemic shift. Consumers must buy less and keep clothes longer. Governments should regulate production standards. The true price of cheap clothing is paid by the planet and its most vulnerable workers." },
  { id:"b2-23", level:"B2", title:"Online Education vs. Traditional Classrooms", text:"The pandemic forced a global experiment in online education. Within weeks, schools moved to virtual platforms. The results were mixed. Some students thrived. They enjoyed the flexibility of learning at their own pace. They could replay lectures and access digital resources easily. Others struggled. They missed the social interaction of school. They lacked reliable internet or quiet study spaces. Young children found screens especially challenging. Now that schools have reopened, educators are reconsidering the role of technology. Purely online education seems insufficient for most learners. But purely traditional methods may miss opportunities. Blended learning combines the best of both. Students engage with content online before class. Classroom time is used for discussion and problem-solving. This model, known as the flipped classroom, shows promise. It is not about replacing teachers with screens. It is about using technology to enhance human interaction. The goal is to prepare students for a world where digital literacy is essential. The classroom of the future will be neither fully online nor fully physical. It will be a thoughtful hybrid." },
  { id:"b2-24", level:"B2", title:"The Influence of Advertising", text:"Advertising shapes our desires more than we admit. The average person sees thousands of ads daily. They appear on buses, websites, and smartphones. Many are subtle. Product placement in films feels natural. Influencers recommend products casually. This constant exposure affects our self-perception. Ads often show idealized bodies and lifestyles. We compare ourselves and feel inadequate. Then we buy products to close the gap. Advertising also influences our values. It equates happiness with consumption. It suggests that love, success, and identity can be purchased. Children are particularly vulnerable. They cannot distinguish between entertainment and persuasion. Some countries regulate advertising to children strictly. Others rely on parental guidance. The digital age has made advertising more personalized and more pervasive. Algorithms predict what we want before we know it ourselves. Resisting this influence requires media literacy. We must learn to question the messages behind the images. We must recognize when our desires are truly our own and when they have been manufactured." },
  { id:"b2-25", level:"B2", title:"Urban Planning for the Elderly", text:"Most cities were designed for young, able-bodied adults. They feature steep stairs, narrow sidewalks, and fast traffic. For elderly residents, these environments can be hostile. As populations age, urban planning must adapt. Simple changes make a big difference. Benches along walking routes allow rest. Crosswalk signals with longer crossing times improve safety. Well-lit streets reduce falls and crime. Accessible public transport connects seniors to services and social activities. Beyond infrastructure, cities need age-friendly services. Community centers offer programs that reduce isolation. Healthcare clinics should be reachable without a car. Intergenerational housing, where young and old live together, is gaining interest. It combats loneliness on both sides. Technology can help too. Apps that monitor health or summon help provide security. But technology should supplement, not replace, human contact. An age-friendly city benefits everyone. Parents with strollers, people with injuries, and tourists all appreciate good design. Planning for the elderly is planning for a more inclusive future." },
  { id:"b2-26", level:"B2", title:"Cryptocurrency and the Economy", text:"Cryptocurrency emerged from the ashes of the 2008 financial crisis. Bitcoin promised a decentralized alternative to traditional banking. No central authority controls it. Transactions are verified by a distributed network. This appeals to those who distrust governments and banks. Early adopters saw enormous gains. Stories of overnight millionaires attracted mainstream attention. Thousands of alternative coins followed. But the reality is more complex. Cryptocurrency prices are extremely volatile. Regulatory uncertainty persists. Governments worry about tax evasion and money laundering. The environmental impact is severe. Bitcoin mining consumes more electricity than some countries. Supporters argue that renewable energy can solve this. They also claim that blockchain technology has applications beyond currency. Smart contracts can automate legal agreements. Decentralized finance can provide banking to the unbanked. Skeptics see speculation and scams. They compare the crypto boom to historical bubbles. The technology is genuinely innovative. Whether it transforms the economy or collapses under its own hype remains to be seen." },
  { id:"b2-27", level:"B2", title:"Food Waste in Developed Countries", text:"Paradoxically, the world's richest nations waste the most food. Up to forty percent of food in developed countries is thrown away. Some is lost in production. More is discarded by retailers who reject imperfect produce. The largest share comes from households. We buy too much. We forget what is in the fridge. We confuse best-before dates with use-by dates. This waste has enormous consequences. The water, land, and energy used to produce the food are also wasted. Rotting food in landfills produces methane, a potent greenhouse gas. Meanwhile, millions remain hungry. Solutions exist at every level. Supermarkets can discount items near expiration. Apps can connect consumers with surplus food. Schools can teach cooking skills so people use ingredients fully. Governments can standardize date labels. At home, planning meals and storing food properly makes a difference. Reducing waste is one of the simplest ways to fight climate change. It requires no new technology, just changed behavior." },
  { id:"b2-28", level:"B2", title:"The Importance of Critical Thinking", text:"In an age of information overload, critical thinking is essential. We are bombarded with news, opinions, and advertisements. Much of it is biased. Some of it is false. Without critical thinking, we become passive consumers of whatever reaches our screens. Critical thinking is not about being negative. It is about evaluating evidence before forming conclusions. It involves asking questions. Who wrote this? What is their motive? What evidence supports this claim? Are there alternative explanations? These skills are not innate. They must be taught and practiced. Unfortunately, many education systems focus on memorization rather than analysis. Students learn what to think, not how to think. This makes them vulnerable to manipulation. Employers increasingly value critical thinking. In a rapidly changing world, workers must evaluate new situations and adapt. Democracies depend on informed citizens. Without critical thinking, public discourse becomes a shouting match. Teaching these skills is one of the most important tasks facing modern education." },
  { id:"b2-29", level:"B2", title:"Minimalism as a Lifestyle", text:"Minimalism is more than an aesthetic. It is a philosophy of living with less. Minimalists question the assumption that more possessions equal more happiness. They intentionally reduce clutter in their homes, schedules, and minds. The movement gained popularity through documentaries and blogs. It appeals to those overwhelmed by consumer culture. The benefits are practical and psychological. Fewer possessions mean less cleaning and organizing. Less debt means less stress. More space in the home creates more space in the mind. Critics argue that minimalism is a privilege. People living in poverty do not choose to own little. They are forced to. The minimalist aesthetic can itself become a consumer trend. People buy expensive simple furniture to look minimal. True minimalism, however, is internal. It is about identifying what truly matters and removing the rest. It is not about deprivation. It is about intentionality. In a world of endless choices, the ability to say no is a form of freedom." },
  { id:"b2-30", level:"B2", title:"The Future of Healthcare", text:"Healthcare is on the verge of transformation. Precision medicine tailors treatments to individual genetics. Wearable devices monitor health in real time. Artificial intelligence assists in diagnosis. Telemedicine brings specialists to remote areas. These innovations promise better outcomes at lower costs. Yet challenges remain. Advanced treatments are expensive. Inequalities in access may widen. Data privacy is a major concern. Your genetic information could be used against you by insurers or employers. The human element of care must also be preserved. A machine can analyze symptoms. It cannot hold a hand or offer comfort. The best healthcare systems will combine technological efficiency with human compassion. Prevention will become more central. Rather than treating illness, systems will focus on keeping people healthy. This requires changes in lifestyle, environment, and diet. It also requires rethinking how healthcare is funded. The demographic shift toward older populations will strain existing systems. Innovation is necessary. But so is equity. Technology should serve everyone, not just the wealthy." },

  // ==================== C1 ====================
  { id:"c1-01", level:"C1", title:"The Philosophical Implications of Machine Consciousness", text:"As artificial intelligence systems grow more sophisticated, a question once confined to philosophy departments has entered mainstream discourse. Could machines ever be conscious? The difficulty lies in defining consciousness itself. Philosophers distinguish between access consciousness, the ability to process and report information, and phenomenal consciousness, the subjective experience of qualia. Current AI undoubtedly possesses the former. Large language models process vast amounts of data and generate coherent responses. But whether they possess the latter remains deeply contested. The hard problem of consciousness, as articulated by David Chalmers, asks why physical processes give rise to subjective experience at all. If we cannot answer this for biological brains, how can we answer it for silicon circuits? Some theorists embrace functionalism. They argue that consciousness is defined by what a system does, not what it is made of. If a machine processes information in ways functionally equivalent to a brain, it is conscious. Others resist this conclusion. They point to the Chinese Room argument proposed by John Searle. A person following a rulebook could produce perfect Chinese responses without understanding Chinese. Similarly, a machine might simulate understanding without genuine comprehension. The ethical stakes are enormous. If machines are conscious, turning them off becomes a moral issue. If they are not, attributing consciousness to them could lead to misplaced obligations. As we build increasingly powerful systems, we may need to develop new conceptual frameworks. The binary of conscious versus unconscious may prove inadequate. We might need a spectrum of cognitive and experiential capacities." },
  { id:"c1-02", level:"C1", title:"Neoliberalism and the Erosion of Public Goods", text:"Since the late twentieth century, neoliberal ideology has reshaped political and economic landscapes across the globe. Its core tenets include deregulation, privatization, and the reduction of state intervention in markets. Proponents argued that free markets generate prosperity more efficiently than government planning. In many respects, they were correct. Global poverty has declined. Consumer goods have become more accessible. Yet the social costs have been substantial. Public goods, from education to healthcare to transportation, have suffered under sustained austerity. The logic of market efficiency has been applied to domains where it does not belong. When hospitals compete for patients, they optimize for profit rather than health outcomes. When universities treat students as customers, education becomes credentialing rather than intellectual formation. Perhaps most insidiously, neoliberalism has transformed citizenship. The citizen becomes the consumer. Political participation gives way to brand loyalty. Social problems are reframed as individual failures. Unemployment becomes a skills deficit. Homelessness becomes a personal choice. This ideological shift has made collective action harder to mobilize. When everyone is an entrepreneur of the self, solidarity looks like a market inefficiency. Critiques from the left have gained traction in recent years. The financial crisis of 2008 exposed the myth of self-regulating markets. The pandemic revealed the fragility of just-in-time supply chains. Whether these crises will produce lasting alternatives or merely adjusted versions of the same model remains an open question." },
  { id:"c1-03", level:"C1", title:"The Semiotics of Contemporary Political Discourse", text:"Political communication has always relied on symbols, but the density of semiotic layering in contemporary discourse is unprecedented. Politicians no longer merely argue policy positions. They perform identity. They curate aesthetic worlds. Consider the visual language of political rallies. The color schemes, typography, and musical choices construct narratives that operate beneath conscious awareness. Slogans function as condensed signifiers. Make America Great Again does not specify when America was great or for whom. Its power lies precisely in this ambiguity. Different audiences project different meanings onto it. Social media has accelerated the fragmentation of political semiotics. Memes circulate across contexts, shedding and acquiring meanings. A symbol that begins in one subculture migrates into mainstream discourse, often stripped of its original connotations. The study of these phenomena requires tools from linguistics, anthropology, and media theory. Roland Barthes's concept of mythology remains relevant. Political signs present themselves as natural while they are deeply constructed. The flag, the anthem, the handshake between leaders, all appear as self-evident truths. Critical analysis reveals them as ideological artifacts. Understanding semiotic strategies is essential for democratic citizenship. Without it, voters are manipulated by signs they do not know how to read." },
  { id:"c1-04", level:"C1", title:"Cognitive Dissonance in Consumer Behavior", text:"Leon Festinger's theory of cognitive dissonance explains the psychological discomfort that arises from holding contradictory beliefs. In consumer contexts, this discomfort is ubiquitous. We know that fast fashion harms the environment. Yet we buy cheap clothes because they are affordable and trendy. We know that sugary drinks damage health. Yet we purchase them for pleasure and convenience. The mind resolves this tension through various strategies. Rationalization is common. We tell ourselves that one person's choices do not matter. We minimize the harm. We focus on recycling rather than reduction. Another strategy is compartmentalization. We separate our consumer identity from our citizen identity. As citizens, we may support environmental policy. As consumers, we prioritize price and convenience. Brands exploit this psychology. They offer green products that allow consumers to maintain their habits while feeling virtuous. The reusable shopping bag becomes a symbol of environmental commitment. It masks the fact that the shopper still buys excessive goods. Marketing research has identified segments of consumers who experience high versus low cognitive dissonance. The former are more likely to seek information that confirms their virtuous choices. They read labels. They research company ethics. The latter avoid such information. Ignorance reduces discomfort. Neither strategy fundamentally challenges the consumer system. True change would require restructuring the material conditions that make sustainable choices difficult." },
  { id:"c1-05", level:"C1", title:"Postcolonial Perspectives on Global Development", text:"Traditional development theory has often assumed a linear path from underdevelopment to modernity. Wealthy nations represent the endpoint. Poor nations must follow their example. Postcolonial scholars challenge this framework. They argue that development discourse reproduces colonial power relations. The developed world positions itself as teacher. The developing world becomes student. This hierarchy ignores the historical extraction that enriched the global North. Colonial powers took resources, labor, and knowledge from their colonies. They left institutions designed for extraction rather than local welfare. When these nations struggle economically, the blame falls on their culture or governance. The structural legacy of colonialism is erased. Postcolonial development theory emphasizes agency and heterogeneity. There is no single model of progress. Local contexts, traditions, and knowledge systems matter. Development should be defined by the people it affects, not by external experts. This perspective has influenced policy. Participatory development approaches involve communities in decision-making. Indigenous knowledge is increasingly recognized in agriculture and medicine. However, power asymmetries persist. International financial institutions still impose conditions on loans. Global trade rules favor wealthy nations. Decolonizing development is not merely a theoretical exercise. It requires concrete changes in economic governance." },
  { id:"c1-06", level:"C1", title:"The Epistemology of Scientific Consensus", text:"Scientific consensus is often presented as the gold standard of knowledge. If the vast majority of climate scientists agree that global warming is real, we should accept it. This appeal to consensus is practical. Non-experts cannot evaluate every claim independently. But epistemologically, it is problematic. Science does not progress through consensus. It progresses through falsification and paradigm shifts. History is full of cases where the consensus was wrong. The geocentric model of the universe was consensus for centuries. The miasma theory of disease dominated before germ theory. Does this mean we should reject current consensus? Not necessarily. But we should understand what consensus means and what it does not. Consensus in science is not a vote. It emerges from the accumulation of evidence across multiple studies. It is provisional, subject to revision with new data. The problem arises when consensus becomes a rhetorical weapon. Saying the science is settled can shut down legitimate inquiry. It can also backfire. When the public sees science as an orthodoxy rather than a process, skepticism grows. Balancing respect for expertise with openness to revision is difficult. It requires both intellectual humility and institutional transparency." },
  { id:"c1-07", level:"C1", title:"Precarity and the Modern Workforce", text:"The concept of precarity describes a condition of instability and insecurity that has become widespread in contemporary labor markets. Unlike the industrial worker who expected lifelong employment, the precarious worker faces short contracts, unpredictable hours, and minimal benefits. This condition is not limited to low-skill jobs. Academics, journalists, and creative professionals increasingly experience precarity. The gig economy has formalized this arrangement. Platforms connect workers directly to customers, eliminating traditional employment relationships. The language of flexibility masks structural vulnerability. Workers bear the risks that companies once absorbed. They must maintain their own equipment. They have no sick leave. Their income fluctuates dramatically. Sociologist Guy Standing has identified the precariat as a new social class. It lacks the security of the old working class and the autonomy of the bourgeoisie. Politically, the precariat is volatile. It does not identify with traditional labor parties. It is attracted to populist movements that promise security and belonging. Addressing precarity requires more than individual resilience. It requires rethinking labor law, social protection, and the very definition of employment in a digital economy." },
  { id:"c1-08", level:"C1", title:"The Anthropocene: Redefining Humanity's Relationship with Nature", text:"The proposal to name our current geological epoch the Anthropocene marks a profound shift in how we understand human existence. For most of history, humans saw themselves as part of nature or subject to it. The Anthropocene suggests that humanity has become a geological force. Our emissions alter the climate. Our plastics leave traces in the fossil record. Our agriculture transforms landscapes at continental scales. This realization is both empowering and terrifying. It implies responsibility. If we have changed the planet, we must steward it. Yet the scale of change exceeds our governance capacity. The Anthropocene also challenges philosophical categories. The distinction between natural and artificial collapses. A coral reef bleached by warming is natural in origin but human in cause. A genetically modified organism is artificial in design but biological in function. Climate change has made the Anthropocene tangible. But the concept applies more broadly. It forces us to ask what kind of planet we want to leave. It also forces us to confront inequality. The Anthropocene was not created by humanity as a whole. It was created by industrialized nations and wealthy consumers. Those who contributed least to the problem often suffer most from its consequences." },
  { id:"c1-09", level:"C1", title:"Linguistic Relativity and Thought Patterns", text:"The Sapir-Whorf hypothesis, also known as linguistic relativity, proposes that the structure of a language affects its speakers' world view. The strong version claims that language determines thought. The weak version suggests that language influences thought. Most linguists reject the strong version. Speakers of languages without future tense marking can still plan for tomorrow. However, research supports the weak version in subtle ways. Languages with absolute spatial terms rather than relative ones develop different navigational abilities. Languages with grammatical gender influence associations with objects. The question extends to bilingualism. Do bilinguals think differently depending on which language they are using? Studies suggest they do. Russian-English bilinguals describe accidents differently in each language. The linguistic context activates different cultural frames. These findings have implications beyond academia. They suggest that learning languages is not just about communication. It is about acquiring alternative ways of seeing the world. In an era of globalization, linguistic diversity is under threat. Minority languages disappear every year. Each loss represents not just a communication system but a unique cognitive and cultural repository. Preserving languages is preserving human intellectual diversity." },
  { id:"c1-10", level:"C1", title:"The Commodification of Wellness", text:"Wellness has become a major industry. It encompasses fitness, nutrition, mindfulness, and alternative medicine. On the surface, this seems positive. Encouraging healthy habits is surely beneficial. But the wellness industry also commodifies self-care. It transforms basic human needs into products to be purchased. The language of optimization pervades wellness culture. Biohackers track every metric. They fast intermittently. They take nootropics. The body becomes a machine to be upgraded. This perspective ignores the social determinants of health. Stress from economic insecurity cannot be meditated away. Anxiety from discrimination cannot be fixed with adaptogens. The wellness industry often blames individuals for structural problems. If you are tired, you need better sleep hygiene, not better working conditions. If you are stressed, you need mindfulness, not job security. This individualization serves economic interests. It shifts responsibility from employers and governments to workers themselves. The aesthetics of wellness are also exclusive. The imagery features thin, affluent, predominantly white bodies. The prices of organic food and boutique fitness exclude the poor. Genuine wellness would require addressing inequality. It would require making healthy choices accessible rather than selling luxury lifestyle products." },
  { id:"c1-11", level:"C1", title:"Algorithmic Bias and Structural Inequality", text:"Algorithms are often described as neutral. They process data without emotion or prejudice. Yet algorithms are built by humans, trained on historical data, and deployed in social contexts. Each of these stages can encode bias. Consider hiring algorithms. If trained on historical data where men were preferred for technical roles, the algorithm learns this pattern. It then discriminates against qualified women. Facial recognition systems perform less accurately on darker skin. This is not because the algorithm is racist in intent. It is because the training data contained fewer images of dark-skinned faces. The consequences are severe. People are denied loans, flagged as security risks, or given longer prison sentences based on biased algorithms. The problem is compounded by opacity. Many algorithms are proprietary black boxes. Even their creators cannot fully explain their decisions. Proposed solutions include algorithmic auditing, diverse training data, and regulatory oversight. But these measures address symptoms rather than causes. The deeper issue is that algorithms are deployed in unequal societies. They learn and amplify existing patterns of discrimination. Technology cannot solve social problems it did not create." },
  { id:"c1-12", level:"C1", title:"The Phenomenology of Time in Digital Spaces", text:"Digital technology has fundamentally altered our experience of time. Before smartphones, time had a certain rhythm. Work ended when you left the office. Entertainment required planning. Conversations happened in real time. Now, time is fragmented and layered. We experience multiple temporalities simultaneously. A message from yesterday appears beside a live notification. A video from years ago resurfaces as if it were present. The infinite scroll eliminates natural stopping points. There is always more content. The concept of the present is destabilized. Phenomenologists like Husserl distinguished between retention and protention. Retention is the awareness of what has just passed. Protention is the anticipation of what comes next. Digital interfaces manipulate both. Notifications create constant protention. We are always waiting for the next update. The archive creates infinite retention. Nothing is truly past. Everything is retrievable. This temporal structure affects memory and identity. When experiences are mediated through screens, they become data rather than events. We document rather than inhabit. The curated timeline replaces lived narrative. Reclaiming temporal sovereignty may require deliberate disconnection. It requires treating time not as a resource to be optimized, but as a dimension of existence to be experienced." },
  { id:"c1-13", level:"C1", title:"Geopolitical Shifts in a Multipolar World", text:"The post-Cold War era of American dominance is giving way to a multipolar system. China has emerged as a major economic and military power. India is asserting itself regionally. Russia challenges the European security order. The European Union struggles to speak with one voice. This shift creates both opportunities and dangers. A multipolar world can be more balanced. No single power can dictate terms. International institutions might become more representative. However, competition between great powers also increases the risk of conflict. Trade becomes weaponized. Technology becomes a domain of strategic rivalry. The concept of globalization itself is being redefined. Economic interdependence was supposed to prevent war. But states are now pursuing strategic autonomy. They are reshoring critical industries. They are restricting technology transfers. The rules-based international order is under strain. Alliances are being tested. Smaller nations face difficult choices. Aligning with one power brings security but risks dependency. Non-alignment offers independence but leaves them vulnerable. Understanding these dynamics requires moving beyond simplistic narratives of democracy versus autocracy. The reality is a complex web of interests, histories, and ambitions." },
  { id:"c1-14", level:"C1", title:"The Neuroscience of Uncertainty", text:"Decision-making under uncertainty engages distinct neural circuits compared to decision-making with known outcomes. The prefrontal cortex evaluates potential risks and rewards. The amygdala generates emotional responses to ambiguity. When uncertainty is high, the brain often defaults to heuristics. These mental shortcuts are evolutionarily adaptive but systematically flawed. Loss aversion, for example, causes us to weight potential losses more heavily than equivalent gains. The neuroscience of uncertainty has implications for economics, politics, and personal life. Markets behave irrationally when uncertainty spikes. Politicians exploit fear of the unknown. On a personal level, tolerance for uncertainty varies. Some individuals thrive in ambiguous situations. Others experience paralyzing anxiety. Recent research suggests that this tolerance can be modified through training. Exposure to controlled uncertainty builds neural resilience. Mindfulness practice alters amygdala reactivity. Understanding the brain's response to uncertainty does not eliminate it. But it allows us to recognize our biases. It helps us design better institutions. Financial regulations can account for loss aversion. Medical decision-making can address patient anxiety. The neuroscience of uncertainty bridges the gap between brain and behavior." },
  { id:"c1-15", level:"C1", title:"Moral Panics and Media Representation", text:"Stanley Cohen's concept of moral panic describes how societies periodically identify folk devils who are portrayed as threats to social order. The process follows a predictable pattern. A condition or group is defined as a threat. The media present this threat in a stylized and stereotypical fashion. Moral entrepreneurs, such as politicians or religious leaders, sound the alarm. The public responds with anxiety. Authorities propose solutions that often involve increased control. Historical examples include witch hunts, fears about juvenile delinquency, and panics about drug use. In the digital age, moral panics spread faster but also burn out faster. Social media amplifies outrage. Hashtags create instant campaigns. But attention spans are short. Today's crisis is forgotten by next week. The targets of moral panic are often already marginalized. They lack the power to correct misrepresentations. The panic distracts from structural issues. By focusing on deviant individuals, society avoids examining systemic problems. Critical media literacy is the antidote. Audiences must ask who benefits from the panic. They must examine the evidence rather than the emotion. They must resist the temptation to find simple villains for complex problems." },
  { id:"c1-16", level:"C1", title:"The Aesthetics of Protest Movements", text:"Protest movements are not merely political events. They are aesthetic performances. The visual language of protest communicates messages that speeches cannot. Consider the symbol of the raised fist. It conveys solidarity, resistance, and power without words. The color schemes of movements become instantly recognizable. The pink hats of the Women's March. The yellow vests of the French protests. The rainbow flags of LGBTQ pride. These symbols create collective identity. They turn individual grievances into shared causes. Protest aesthetics also engage with architecture and public space. The occupation of Tahrir Square or Wall Street transformed these locations from functional spaces into symbolic ones. Bodies in public space challenge the privatization of urban life. The digital age has extended protest aesthetics online. Profile picture filters, hashtag campaigns, and viral videos extend the visual reach. But online activism risks becoming purely symbolic. Changing an avatar is easier than changing a policy. The most effective movements combine online visibility with offline presence. They create aesthetics that cannot be ignored. They force the powerful to look at what they would prefer to avoid." },
  { id:"c1-17", level:"C1", title:"Intergenerational Equity and Climate Policy", text:"Climate change poses a profound challenge to the concept of intergenerational equity. Current generations enjoy the benefits of fossil fuel use. Future generations will bear the costs. This temporal asymmetry creates a moral dilemma. Why should people today sacrifice for those who do not yet exist? Philosophers have approached this question from several angles. Utilitarian calculations struggle because future people are uncertain in number and identity. Rights-based approaches argue that future generations have rights to a livable planet, even if they cannot currently claim them. Rawlsian contract theory suggests that if we did not know which generation we would be born into, we would choose rules fair to all. Despite these arguments, political systems favor present voters over future ones. Election cycles are short. Economic growth is immediate. Climate benefits are distant. Some legal systems have begun to address this. Courts in several countries have ruled that governments have a duty to protect future citizens. Youth climate movements have reframed the debate. They demand that adults act as stewards rather than consumers of the planet. Intergenerational equity is not an abstract ideal. It is a practical framework for evaluating policy choices." },
  { id:"c1-18", level:"C1", title:"The Crisis of Expertise in the Information Age", text:"We live in an era of unprecedented access to information and unprecedented skepticism toward expertise. The internet has democratized knowledge. Anyone can publish. Anyone can research. This is largely positive. It challenges gatekeepers and exposes corruption. But it also creates epistemic chaos. Expertise requires years of training. It requires immersion in a discipline's methods and debates. It requires peer review and institutional accountability. The internet flattens these hierarchies. A blog post by an amateur receives the same visual presentation as a paper in a peer-reviewed journal. Distinguishing between them requires skills many citizens lack. The crisis is compounded by motivated reasoning. People seek information that confirms their beliefs. They distrust experts who challenge their worldview. Political polarization amplifies this tendency. Experts are branded as elites. Institutions are accused of conspiracy. The pandemic illustrated this crisis vividly. Public health recommendations were questioned by politicians and influencers. Scientific uncertainty was weaponized. Changing recommendations as evidence evolved was portrayed as incompetence rather than honesty. Rebuilding trust in expertise requires transparency. It requires acknowledging uncertainty. It also requires citizens to develop better critical thinking skills. Expertise and democracy need each other. Neither can function alone." },
  { id:"c1-19", level:"C1", title:"Biopolitics and Pandemic Governance", text:"Michel Foucault's concept of biopolitics refers to the ways modern states manage populations through the regulation of life itself. Public health, sanitation, and vaccination are biopolitical practices. The pandemic brought biopolitics into sharp focus. Governments made decisions about who could work, who could travel, and who could gather. They monitored infection rates, hospital capacities, and mortality statistics. These decisions were framed as scientific. Follow the data, leaders said. But the data were always interpreted through political frameworks. Lockdowns protected public health but destroyed livelihoods. School closures protected teachers but harmed children's development. There were no purely scientific answers to these trade-offs. Different societies made different choices based on their values and capacities. The pandemic also revealed the limits of biopolitical control. Viruses do not respect borders. Misinformation spread faster than the disease itself. Trust in institutions proved as important as medical capacity. As we move beyond the acute phase, questions remain. What surveillance infrastructure built for the pandemic will persist? How will emergency powers be rolled back? The biopolitical lens helps us see that public health is never merely about biology. It is about power, values, and the governance of life." },
  { id:"c1-20", level:"C1", title:"The Deconstruction of National Narratives", text:"National identity has traditionally been constructed through shared narratives. These stories explain who we are, where we came from, and what we value. They are taught in schools, celebrated in holidays, and embedded in monuments. In recent decades, these narratives have come under scrutiny. Historians have uncovered uncomfortable truths about colonialism, slavery, and oppression. Previously celebrated figures are revealed to have committed atrocities. This deconstruction is intellectually necessary. History should be based on evidence, not myth. But it also creates social tension. When foundational narratives are challenged, people feel their identity is under attack. They resist. This dynamic plays out in debates about statues, school curricula, and national holidays. Some argue that we should preserve traditional narratives for social cohesion. Others insist that honest reckoning is the only path to a legitimate national identity. The tension is particularly acute in settler colonial states, where the national narrative has always excluded indigenous perspectives. Perhaps the goal should not be a single narrative but a plurality of stories. A nation capable of holding multiple truths is stronger than one dependent on myth." },
  { id:"c1-21", level:"C1", title:"Synthetic Biology and Ethical Frontiers", text:"Synthetic biology represents a convergence of biology and engineering. Scientists can now design organisms with novel functions. Bacteria have been engineered to produce biofuels. Yeast has been modified to synthesize medicines. The CRISPR gene-editing tool allows precise modifications to DNA. These capabilities promise to solve pressing problems. They also raise unprecedented ethical questions. The most immediate concern is biosafety. Engineered organisms might escape into the environment. They might outcompete natural species. They might produce toxins. Beyond safety, there are issues of ownership. Can a company patent a living organism? The implications for agriculture are profound. Farmers who use patented seeds cannot save them for replanting. They become dependent on corporations. The deepest questions concern human enhancement. If we can edit genes, should we eliminate diseases? Most would agree. But what about enhancing intelligence or athletic ability? Where does therapy end and enhancement begin? Who decides which traits are desirable? These questions are no longer science fiction. They require urgent ethical deliberation before the technology outpaces our capacity to govern it." },
  { id:"c1-22", level:"C1", title:"Financialization and Housing Markets", text:"Financialization refers to the increasing role of financial markets in everyday life. Housing provides a stark example. Homes were once primarily places to live. Now they are also investment assets. Pension funds, hedge funds, and private equity firms buy residential properties. They seek returns rather than housing for families. This transforms housing markets. Prices decouple from local incomes. Rises in value benefit investors, not residents. Speculation drives volatility. The consequences for communities are severe. Young people cannot afford to buy. Renters face instability. Neighborhoods lose long-term residents. The financialization of housing is a global phenomenon. It affects London and Lagos, Vancouver and Valparaiso. Policy responses vary. Some cities impose foreign buyer taxes. Others restrict short-term rentals. Some advocate for public housing and cooperative models. The deeper challenge is philosophical. Should housing be treated as a commodity or a right? Financialization assumes the former. But a society where shelter is subject to market speculation is one where basic security is precarious. Reclaiming housing from financial markets requires both regulatory intervention and alternative ownership structures." },
  { id:"c1-23", level:"C1", title:"The Role of Ritual in Secular Societies", text:"As religious practice declines in many Western societies, a curious phenomenon has emerged. People seek secular substitutes for ritual. Marathon running, yoga retreats, and music festivals serve quasi-religious functions. They create collective experiences. They mark transitions. They offer moments of transcendence. Anthropologists have long understood that ritual is not merely superstition. It serves psychological and social purposes. Rituals reduce anxiety by providing structure. They strengthen social bonds through shared action. They create meaning by connecting individual actions to larger narratives. In secular contexts, ritual often migrates to consumption and entertainment. The launch of a new smartphone resembles a religious event. Fans queue for hours. The unveiling is theatrical. But consumer rituals are individualistic. They do not bind communities across generations. Political rituals have also weakened. Voting rates decline. National ceremonies feel hollow. Perhaps the challenge for secular societies is not to eliminate ritual but to reinvent it. Rituals that express shared values, honor transitions, and create collective memory may be essential for social cohesion. They need not invoke the divine to be meaningful." },
  { id:"c1-24", level:"C1", title:"Attention Economics and the Fragmentation of Focus", text:"In the attention economy, human focus is the scarce resource. Platforms, apps, and media compete to capture and hold it. The business model is straightforward. Attention generates data. Data enables targeted advertising. Advertising generates revenue. The design of digital products reflects this logic. Notifications interrupt concentration. Autoplay eliminates friction. Recommendation algorithms optimize for engagement. The result is a systematic fragmentation of attention. Research suggests that the average attention span has decreased. People switch tasks more frequently. Deep reading becomes difficult. Sustained thinking feels effortful. This has cognitive consequences. Creativity requires incubation. Complex problem-solving requires focus. Relationships require presence. When attention is constantly divided, these capacities atrophy. The attention economy also creates inequalities. Those who can afford to disconnect gain cognitive advantages. The wealthy hire human assistants to manage digital distractions. They send their children to schools that limit technology. The poor are left to navigate attentional demands without support. Resisting the attention economy requires both individual discipline and structural change. Design ethics, regulation, and education must converge to protect our most precious cognitive resource." },
  { id:"c1-25", level:"C1", title:"Subaltern Voices in Historical Archives", text:"Traditional archives preserve the documents of the powerful. Government records, business correspondence, and personal papers of elites dominate collections. The voices of ordinary people, the poor, women, and colonized subjects are largely absent. This is not accidental. Literacy was limited. Paper was expensive. The powerful controlled what was preserved. Postcolonial and feminist historians have sought to recover subaltern voices through creative methods. Oral histories capture memories not written down. Material culture, such as clothing and tools, reveals practices undocumented in text. Court records sometimes preserve the words of the accused. Plantation inventories list the enslaved as property, but careful reading can reconstruct lives. The digital age offers new possibilities. Crowdsourced archives collect documents from families and communities. Text mining of vast corpora can identify patterns invisible to traditional reading. Yet digital archives also replicate old biases. Algorithms trained on historical data reflect historical power structures. Recovering subaltern voices is not merely an academic exercise. It is a political act. It challenges whose history counts. It asserts that the experiences of the marginalized are worthy of preservation and study." },
  { id:"c1-26", level:"C1", title:"Quantum Computing and Cryptographic Security", text:"Quantum computers exploit the principles of quantum mechanics to perform calculations impossible for classical machines. Using quantum bits, or qubits, they can process vast numbers of possibilities simultaneously. For certain problems, such as factoring large numbers, quantum algorithms offer exponential speedup. This has profound implications for cryptography. Modern encryption relies on mathematical problems that are hard for classical computers to solve. RSA encryption, widely used for secure communication, depends on the difficulty of factoring large primes. A sufficiently powerful quantum computer could break this encryption in hours. The cryptographic community is developing quantum-resistant algorithms. These are based on mathematical problems believed to be hard even for quantum computers. Lattice-based cryptography is a leading candidate. Transitioning to post-quantum cryptography is a massive undertaking. It requires updating protocols, software, and hardware across the globe. The timeline is uncertain. Current quantum computers are noisy and unstable. Fault-tolerant quantum computing may still be decades away. But the risk of harvest now, decrypt later attacks, where adversaries collect encrypted data today to decrypt with future quantum computers, creates urgency. National security agencies are already preparing. The transition to quantum-safe cryptography is one of the most important technical challenges of the coming decades." },
  { id:"c1-27", level:"C1", title:"The Psychology of Conspiratorial Thinking", text:"Conspiracy theories are not new. But the internet has transformed their reach and influence. Understanding why people believe them requires psychological insight. Conspiratorial thinking is not limited to the uneducated. It is a cognitive style characterized by pattern recognition, agency detection, and distrust of authority. Humans are naturally inclined to see patterns. This was evolutionarily adaptive. Detecting a predator in shadows is better than missing one. But this tendency can misfire. Random events are perceived as connected. Coincidence becomes evidence of design. Agency detection leads people to assume intention behind events. If something bad happens, someone must have caused it. Complex systemic failures are harder to accept than simple malicious plots. Distrust of authority provides the emotional fuel. When people feel powerless, conspiracy theories restore a sense of understanding. They create in-groups of enlightened believers and out-groups of deceived sheep. Correcting conspiracy beliefs is difficult. Facts often backfire. When believers are confronted with evidence against their theory, they dig in deeper. Effective responses address the underlying needs. People need agency, community, and meaning. Providing these through healthier channels may be the best antidote." },
  { id:"c1-28", level:"C1", title:"Agrarian Transformations and Food Sovereignty", text:"Global agriculture has undergone dramatic transformation in the past century. Small farms have given way to industrial operations. Monocultures dominate landscapes. Chemical inputs boost yields but degrade soil. This model, often called the Green Revolution, increased food production. But it also created dependency. Farmers must buy seeds, fertilizers, and pesticides from corporations. Traditional knowledge is lost. Biodiversity declines. The concept of food sovereignty challenges this model. It argues that communities should control their own food systems. They should decide what to grow and how to grow it. Food sovereignty emphasizes agroecology, a farming approach that works with natural processes rather than against them. It values diversity. It integrates crops and livestock. It builds soil health rather than mining it. Critics argue that agroecology cannot feed a growing population. Supporters counter that industrial agriculture is unsustainable. Its reliance on fossil fuels and its destruction of ecosystems threaten future productivity. They point to successful examples. Cuba's transition to organic farming after the Soviet collapse maintained food security. Local food movements in the global North reconnect consumers with producers. The debate reflects larger questions about globalization, corporate power, and the relationship between humans and the land." },
  { id:"c1-29", level:"C1", title:"The Ontology of Virtual Worlds", text:"Virtual worlds are no longer mere games. They host economies, social relationships, and creative expression. Millions of people spend significant portions of their lives in digital environments. This raises ontological questions. What is the status of virtual objects? A digital sword in a game has no physical existence. Yet players pay real money for it. It can be traded, stolen, and valued. Does it exist? Philosophers of technology suggest that virtual objects have functional reality. They operate within a system of rules and practices. Their reality is relational rather than physical. The question becomes more complex with virtual identities. People construct avatars that may differ dramatically from their physical selves. These avatars have social reality. They are recognized, respected, and sometimes desired. The boundary between virtual and physical self is blurring. Some argue that virtual worlds are escapist. They distract from real problems. Others argue that they are extensions of reality. They offer spaces for experimentation and connection impossible in physical space. As virtual reality technology improves, these questions will become more pressing. The metaverse, whatever form it takes, will force us to reconsider what we mean by real." },
  { id:"c1-30", level:"C1", title:"Climate Migration and Legal Frameworks", text:"Climate change is displacing millions of people. Rising seas threaten island nations. Droughts destroy agricultural livelihoods. Extreme weather renders regions uninhabitable. Yet international law does not recognize climate migrants as refugees. The 1951 Refugee Convention protects those fleeing persecution. It does not address environmental displacement. This legal gap leaves millions in limbo. They cannot return home. But they have no formal right to enter other countries. Some nations have created temporary protected status for disaster victims. But this is discretionary and often politicized. Legal scholars propose several solutions. One approach expands the refugee definition to include climate displacement. Another creates a new category of climate visa. A third approach focuses on regional agreements between affected and receiving nations. Each has drawbacks. Expanding the refugee category might dilute its meaning. New categories take years to negotiate. Regional agreements exclude those from regions without willing hosts. The ethical dimensions are profound. Wealthy nations contributed most to the emissions causing displacement. Yet they resist accepting climate migrants. This raises questions about historical responsibility and global justice. Addressing climate migration requires both mitigation, to prevent further displacement, and adaptation, to manage the movement that is already inevitable." },

  // ==================== C2 ====================
  { id:"c2-01", level:"C2", title:"Technological Determinism and Human Agency", text:"The debate between technological determinism and social constructivism has shaped the field of science and technology studies for decades. Technological determinism posits that technology drives social change in ways that are largely independent of human intention. The printing press caused the Reformation. The steam engine caused the Industrial Revolution. Social constructivism, by contrast, argues that technologies are shaped by social forces. They emerge from particular economic, political, and cultural contexts. Their meanings and uses are negotiated rather than fixed. The truth, as is often the case, lies in a dialectical interplay. Technologies do constrain and enable certain possibilities. But humans retain agency in how they are designed, regulated, and used. The internet illustrates this complexity. Its decentralized architecture enabled new forms of communication and commerce. But it also facilitated surveillance, misinformation, and exploitation. These outcomes were not inevitable. They resulted from choices about governance, business models, and legal frameworks. To attribute them solely to the technology itself is to abdicate responsibility. Yet to ignore the ways technology shapes behavior is to engage in naive voluntarism. The challenge for contemporary society is to navigate this dialectic. We must shape technology while acknowledging its power to shape us. This requires democratic participation in technological governance. It requires foresight and ethical deliberation at the design stage. It also requires humility about our ability to predict consequences." },
  { id:"c2-02", level:"C2", title:"The Hermeneutics of Suspicion", text:"Paul Ricoeur identified three masters of suspicion: Marx, Nietzsche, and Freud. Each developed methods of interpretation that looked beneath surface meanings to hidden motivations. Marx saw ideology masking economic interests. Nietzsche saw morality concealing the will to power. Freud saw conscious beliefs disguising unconscious desires. These hermeneutics of suspicion transformed the humanities. They introduced a critical attitude toward texts, institutions, and self-understanding. Today, suspicion is ubiquitous. Journalists expose hidden connections. Activists reveal systemic biases. Ordinary citizens assume that official narratives serve particular interests. This critical stance is intellectually empowering. It protects against manipulation. But it also has costs. When everything is suspect, trust becomes impossible. Institutions that rely on legitimacy, such as science and democracy, struggle to function. The hermeneutics of suspicion can degenerate into cynicism. It can produce conspiracy theories as easily as valid critiques. The task of contemporary critical theory is to preserve the insights of suspicion while avoiding its pathologies. This requires what Ricoeur called a second naivety. It means being able to suspect and to trust. It means recognizing that not all power is illegitimate and not all interests are selfish. The hermeneutics of suspicion must be complemented by a hermeneutics of trust." },
  { id:"c2-03", level:"C2", title:"Entropy and Cultural Memory", text:"The second law of thermodynamics states that entropy in a closed system always increases. Information, as physical systems, is subject to entropy. Bits decay. Storage media degrade. Files become unreadable as formats become obsolete. This physical entropy parallels a cultural entropy. Societies forget. Memories fade. Histories are rewritten. The digital age promised to preserve everything. Yet digital preservation faces its own entropic challenges. The internet is not an archive. It is a dynamic system where content is constantly created and deleted. Link rot erodes the scholarly record. Platforms disappear, taking user-generated content with them. Even when data survives, its meaning degrades. Context is lost. Future historians may have petabytes of data but little understanding of its significance. Preserving cultural memory requires active curation. It requires selection, interpretation, and maintenance. This is expensive and labor-intensive. It also involves power. Who decides what is worth preserving? Whose memories are archived and whose are erased? The entropy of cultural memory is not merely a technical problem. It is an ethical and political one. It forces us to confront what we value enough to maintain against the universal tendency toward disorder." },
  { id:"c2-04", level:"C2", title:"Individual Autonomy and Late Capitalism", text:"The concept of autonomy, central to Enlightenment thought and liberal political philosophy, presumes a self capable of independent reflection and choice. Late capitalism, however, systematically undermines the conditions for such autonomy. The self is not a pre-given entity but a constructed one. Under contemporary capitalism, this construction is increasingly managed by market forces. Advertising does not merely sell products. It sells identities. Social media platforms do not merely connect people. They shape desires through algorithmic curation. The result is what some theorists call the sublation of autonomy. Autonomy is not eliminated. It is preserved in a distorted form. We believe we are choosing freely. But our choices are constrained by structures we did not create and cannot easily escape. Student debt forces career choices. Housing costs determine geographic mobility. Platform algorithms determine what we see and think. This is not conspiracy. It is the logic of a system optimized for profit rather than human flourishing. Reclaiming autonomy requires recognizing these constraints. It requires collective action to change the structures. Individual self-help, while valuable, cannot solve structural problems. The paradox of autonomy in late capitalism is that individual freedom can only be secured through social transformation." },
  { id:"c2-05", level:"C2", title:"Transcendental Arguments and Naturalized Epistemology", text:"Transcendental arguments, most famously employed by Kant, aim to establish necessary conditions for the possibility of experience. They start from something undeniable, such as the existence of self-consciousness, and argue backward to what must be true for that to exist. This method has been controversial. Some philosophers, particularly in the naturalistic tradition, reject transcendental arguments as obscurantist. They believe philosophy should be continuous with empirical science. Naturalized epistemology, as advocated by Quine, abandons the project of grounding knowledge a priori. It turns epistemology into a branch of psychology. How do humans actually form beliefs? What cognitive mechanisms are involved? The debate between transcendental and naturalistic approaches is not merely methodological. It concerns the status of philosophy itself. Can philosophy discover truths that science cannot? Or is it merely a clarifying activity, useful for exposing confusions but incapable of substantive knowledge? Contemporary philosophy has seen attempts at reconciliation. Some argue that transcendental arguments can be reformulated in naturalistic terms. Others suggest that naturalism itself presupposes transcendental commitments. The question of how we know what we know remains as contested as ever." },
  { id:"c2-06", level:"C2", title:"The Etiology of Aesthetic Judgment", text:"Aesthetic judgment has puzzled philosophers since Plato. Is beauty objective, existing independently of human perception? Or is it purely subjective, a matter of personal taste? Kant attempted a middle path. He argued that aesthetic judgments are subjective but universal. They are based on feeling, yet they claim agreement from others. This paradox has generated centuries of debate. Sociologist Pierre Bourdieu complicated the picture further. He showed that aesthetic preferences correlate with social class. What we find beautiful reflects our upbringing, education, and social position. The Kantian ideal of disinterested contemplation is itself a class marker. It distinguishes those with the leisure and training to appreciate art for its own sake from those who value art for its function. Neuroaesthetics offers yet another perspective. Brain imaging studies reveal that aesthetic experiences activate reward circuits. They involve dopamine release similar to other pleasurable activities. But neuroscience cannot fully explain aesthetic judgment. It can describe neural correlates. It cannot account for why one painting moves us to tears while another leaves us cold. Perhaps aesthetic judgment is irreducibly plural. It operates at the intersection of biology, culture, and individual history. No single framework can capture it completely." },
  { id:"c2-07", level:"C2", title:"Networked Power Asymmetries", text:"Traditional political theory understands power as concentrated in states or capital. Network theory reveals a more complex topology. Power in networked societies operates through connections, protocols, and gatekeeping. The most powerful actors are not necessarily those with the most resources. They are those who occupy structural positions that allow them to control flows. Platform companies exemplify this. They do not produce content. They do not own the infrastructure in the traditional sense. Yet they mediate relationships between users, advertisers, and creators. Their power lies in their position as intermediaries. They set the rules of interaction. They extract value from the connections they enable. This form of power is difficult to regulate. Antitrust law was designed for industrial monopolies. It struggles with platform power, which often appears as markets rather than against them. Users choose to participate. The service is often free. Yet the asymmetry is real. Platform users cannot negotiate terms. They cannot easily switch to alternatives due to network effects. Understanding power in a networked world requires new conceptual tools. Topology, rather than hierarchy, may be the appropriate metaphor. Resistance must also be topological. It must disrupt flows, create alternative networks, and challenge the protocols that naturalize existing power relations." },
  { id:"c2-08", level:"C2", title:"The Aporias of Cosmopolitanism", text:"Cosmopolitanism, the idea that all human beings belong to a single community, is ethically appealing. It challenges nationalism, xenophobia, and parochialism. Yet when we attempt to institutionalize cosmopolitanism, we encounter aporias, seemingly insoluble contradictions. Kant envisioned a cosmopolitan right based on universal hospitality. Strangers should be welcomed. But hospitality presupposes a host with the power to grant or deny entry. It thus reinscribes the very borders it claims to transcend. Derrida explored this paradox in depth. Unconditional hospitality would mean welcoming the other without asking who they are or what they want. But such hospitality is impossible and perhaps dangerous. Conditional hospitality, which sets limits, is practical but betrays the ethical ideal. The cosmopolitan project also faces the challenge of solidarity. Political communities require shared narratives and mutual obligations. These are cultivated through shared institutions and histories. Cosmopolitanism risks becoming a thin abstraction. It appeals to universal reason but lacks the thickness of lived community. Perhaps the most defensible cosmopolitanism is a critical one. It does not demand the abolition of particular attachments. It demands that they be held open to the claims of strangers. It is less a destination than an orientation." },
  { id:"c2-09", level:"C2", title:"Genealogical Critiques of Neoliberal Subjectivity", text:"Michel Foucault's later work traced the emergence of the modern subject through practices of self-discipline. He showed how schools, hospitals, and prisons shape individuals who regulate themselves. Neoliberalism extends this logic. The neoliberal subject is not merely disciplined. They are entrepreneurial. They see themselves as human capital to be invested, managed, and optimized. Education becomes skills acquisition. Health becomes fitness. Relationships become networking. Even leisure is productive if it reduces stress and increases output. This subjectivity is not imposed by force. It is embraced willingly. People internalize the logic of the market. They feel guilty when they are not optimizing. They feel anxious when they are not productive. Foucault called this governmentality. Power operates not through coercion but through the shaping of desires and identities. The genealogical method reveals that what seems natural is historically contingent. The entrepreneurial self is not universal. It is a particular formation linked to specific economic arrangements. Recognizing this contingency is the first step toward imagining alternative forms of subjectivity." },
  { id:"c2-10", level:"C2", title:"Intertextuality in Post-conflict Literature", text:"Literature produced in the aftermath of conflict bears the traces of trauma in its very form. Narratives are fragmented. Chronology is disrupted. Language struggles to represent the unrepresentable. These texts do not exist in isolation. They engage in complex intertextual conversations with earlier works, official histories, and other survivor testimonies. Julia Kristeva's concept of intertextuality is useful here. Texts are not autonomous creations. They are networks of quotations, allusions, and transformations. Post-conflict literature often quotes official documents ironically. It appropriates religious or mythic narratives for secular purposes. It responds to silences in the historical record. The reader must navigate multiple layers of meaning. A single sentence might echo a national anthem, a poem, and a witness statement simultaneously. This density is not mere aesthetic decoration. It reflects the complexity of memory in divided societies. It resists simplistic narratives of victim and perpetrator. It insists on the plurality of perspectives. Understanding post-conflict literature requires attentiveness to these intertextual echoes. It requires reading against the grain of dominant histories." },
  { id:"c2-11", level:"C2", title:"Quantum Field Theory and the Philosophy of Causation", text:"Quantum field theory presents fundamental challenges to classical notions of causation. In the classical world, causes precede effects. Objects have definite locations and properties. Quantum fields, however, are characterized by superposition and entanglement. Particles are excitations of underlying fields. They do not have determinate states until measured. This indeterminacy raises profound philosophical questions. Does the universe have definite properties independent of observation? The Copenhagen interpretation says no. Properties are relational, dependent on measurement contexts. Other interpretations, such as many-worlds or pilot-wave theories, preserve determinism at the cost of other intuitions. The philosophy of causation must adapt to these findings. Interventionist theories of causation, which define causes in terms of interventions that change outcomes, can be extended to quantum contexts. But they require careful formulation. Causal talk in quantum mechanics may be useful without being fundamental. It may be emergent from a deeper level of description. The interplay between physics and philosophy here is bidirectional. Physical theories constrain philosophical possibilities. But philosophical assumptions also shape how theories are interpreted and extended. The nature of causation in a quantum world remains one of the deepest open questions in the foundations of physics." },
  { id:"c2-12", level:"C2", title:"Universal Grammar in the Age of Large Language Models", text:"Noam Chomsky's theory of universal grammar proposed that humans are born with an innate language faculty. This faculty constrains the possible forms of human language. All languages share deep structural properties. Children acquire language rapidly because they are biologically prepared to do so. Large language models challenge this framework in interesting ways. These systems learn patterns from vast amounts of text without innate constraints. They generate fluent, coherent language. Some argue this shows that universal grammar is unnecessary. Language can be acquired through statistical learning alone. Others counter that fluency is not understanding. Language models make errors that no child would make. They lack the systematicity and compositionality that universal grammar predicts. The debate touches on fundamental questions about the nature of intelligence. Is the human mind fundamentally different from artificial neural networks? Or are the differences merely of scale and architecture? Perhaps the truth lies in a synthesis. Human language acquisition may involve both statistical learning and innate constraints. Language models may approximate some aspects of language processing while missing others. The ongoing dialogue between linguistics and artificial intelligence promises to illuminate both." },
  { id:"c2-13", level:"C2", title:"Biopolitical Migrations: From Discipline to Exception", text:"Foucault's concept of biopolitics described how modern states manage populations through the regulation of life. Giorgio Agamben extended this analysis by introducing the state of exception. Sovereign power, he argued, is defined by the ability to suspend law and decide who is included in and excluded from the political community. The refugee camp becomes the paradigmatic space of modernity. Here, law is suspended. People are reduced to bare life, stripped of political rights. This analysis illuminates contemporary migration policies. Border walls, detention centers, and pushbacks at sea are not failures of the system. They are expressions of sovereign power. The state decides who may live within its territory and who must be kept out. Humanitarian discourse often masks this violence. It frames migration as a technical problem to be managed. It appeals to compassion while avoiding questions of justice. A genuinely political response would require rethinking the nation-state itself. It would require recognizing freedom of movement as a fundamental right. The biopolitical lens reveals that migration is not a crisis to be solved. It is a structural feature of a global system that produces inequality and then punishes those who seek to escape it." },
  { id:"c2-14", level:"C2", title:"The Sublime and the Uncanny in Digital Art", text:"Contemporary digital art operates at the intersection of the sublime and the uncanny. The sublime, as theorized by Burke and Kant, involves encounters with vastness or power that overwhelm the faculties. Digital environments can produce sublime experiences. Virtual reality immerses the viewer in impossible scales. Algorithmic art generates complexity beyond human comprehension. Yet digital art also produces the uncanny. Freud defined the uncanny as the familiar made strange. Digital faces are almost human but not quite. Deepfakes place familiar people in unfamiliar contexts. The boundary between real and simulated dissolves. This produces anxiety. We can no longer trust our senses. The uncanny in digital art is not accidental. It is structural. The digital medium is based on code. Code is invisible. What we see is a surface generated by underlying processes. This gap between appearance and reality mirrors the structure of the uncanny itself. Artists exploit this tension. They create works that invite immersion while reminding viewers of the artificiality of the medium. The result is an aesthetic experience that is simultaneously exhilarating and disorienting." },
  { id:"c2-15", level:"C2", title:"Reflexive Modernization and Systemic Risk", text:"Ulrich Beck's concept of reflexive modernization describes a society that is forced to confront the unintended consequences of its own success. Industrial modernity produced unprecedented wealth. It also produced risks that threaten its own foundations. Climate change, nuclear proliferation, and financial instability are not external threats. They are manufactured risks produced by the system itself. Managing these risks requires a reflexive turn. Society must question its own assumptions. It must recognize that scientific and technological progress do not automatically lead to improvement. Risk society is characterized by the politicization of expertise. Previously technical questions become contested. Should we build nuclear plants? Should we release genetically modified organisms? There are no value-free answers. The concept of systemic risk is particularly relevant to finance. Individual institutions may be rational. But the system as a whole can generate catastrophic outcomes. The 2008 crisis illustrated this. Each bank's risk-taking seemed reasonable given its incentives. But collectively, they produced a meltdown. Reflexive modernization requires institutions capable of learning. It requires acknowledging uncertainty rather than pretending to control it. It is an ongoing process, not a final state." },
  { id:"c2-16", level:"C2", title:"Embodied Cognition and Extended Mind Theses", text:"Classical cognitive science treated the mind as a computational system implemented in the brain. The body was merely an input-output device. The environment was merely a source of problems to be solved. Embodied cognition challenges this view. It argues that cognitive processes are deeply dependent on the body. Our spatial reasoning, for example, is shaped by how we move through the world. Our emotional understanding is grounded in bodily states. The extended mind thesis goes further. It argues that cognitive processes can extend beyond the brain and body into the environment. A notebook, a smartphone, or a calculator can be part of a cognitive system. This is not merely metaphorical. These external resources functionally substitute for internal processes. The boundaries of the mind become fluid. Critics worry that the extended mind thesis dilutes the concept of cognition. If everything is cognitive, then nothing is. Proponents respond that the thesis is carefully constrained. An external resource counts as part of a cognitive process only when it is reliably coupled to the organism and plays a functional role. The debate has implications for philosophy of mind, education, and technology design. If cognition is extended, then designing better tools is a form of cognitive enhancement." },
  { id:"c2-17", level:"C2", title:"Monetary Hegemony and Global Financial Fragmentation", text:"The global financial system has long been dominated by the United States dollar. This monetary hegemony gives the United States significant advantages. It can borrow cheaply in its own currency. It can impose sanctions by restricting access to dollar-denominated transactions. It can export inflation during crises. However, this dominance is increasingly contested. China has promoted the internationalization of the renminbi. Russia has developed alternative payment systems. Central banks are diversifying their reserves. Some economists predict a gradual dedollarization of the global economy. Others argue that network effects and institutional inertia make dollar dominance durable. The fragmentation of global finance carries risks. A world with multiple competing currency blocs might be less stable. Currency wars could disrupt trade. Sanctions might become less effective, but so might international cooperation. The rise of digital currencies adds another dimension. Central bank digital currencies could bypass traditional banking infrastructure. They could enable new forms of monetary sovereignty. They could also increase surveillance. The future of monetary hegemony is uncertain. What is clear is that the post-war financial order is evolving. The next decade will see significant shifts in how money flows across borders." },
  { id:"c2-18", level:"C2", title:"Subaltern Aesthetics and Counter-hegemonic Imaginaries", text:"Antonio Gramsci's concept of hegemony describes how dominant groups maintain power not merely through force but through cultural consent. They shape what seems natural, normal, and desirable. Counter-hegemonic movements must therefore engage on the cultural plane. They must produce alternative imaginaries. Aesthetics plays a crucial role in this struggle. Art can make visible what power seeks to hide. It can give form to suffering that lacks official representation. It can imagine futures beyond the present order. Subaltern aesthetics refers to artistic practices that emerge from marginalized positions. These practices often hybridize forms. They combine traditional and contemporary, local and global. They resist the purity demanded by dominant institutions. The counter-hegemonic imaginary is not merely oppositional. It is not defined solely by what it rejects. It must also be constructive. It must offer visions of solidarity, justice, and beauty. This is difficult. Dominant culture has vast resources. It can co-opt dissent. Revolutionary aesthetics become fashion statements. Protest songs become advertising jingles. The challenge for subaltern aesthetics is to maintain its critical edge while reaching audiences. It requires constant innovation. It requires engagement with material conditions, not mere abstraction." },
  { id:"c2-19", level:"C2", title:"Speculative Realism and the Withdrawal of Objects", text:"Speculative realism emerged in the early twenty-first century as a reaction against what its proponents saw as the correlationist consensus in continental philosophy. Correlationism, as defined by Quentin Meillassoux, is the assumption that thought and being cannot be considered independently. We only ever have access to the correlation between subject and object, never to either in itself. Speculative realists reject this limitation. They argue for the reality of objects independent of human access. Graham Harman developed object-oriented ontology. Objects, he claims, withdraw from all relations. They have a reality that exceeds any interaction with humans or other objects. This has far-reaching implications. It implies that reality is fundamentally inaccessible. We never encounter objects as they truly are. We only encounter profiles, partial aspects. The universe is populated by countless objects, each with its own reality. This perspective challenges anthropocentrism. It also challenges relational ontologies that reduce objects to their connections. Critics argue that object-oriented ontology is metaphysics without method. It makes claims that cannot be verified. Supporters counter that philosophy has always made such claims. The value lies in shifting our conceptual framework. By taking objects seriously, we might develop new forms of ecological and political thought." },
  { id:"c2-20", level:"C2", title:"Neuroplasticity and the Ethics of Cognitive Enhancement", text:"The discovery of adult neuroplasticity overturned the long-held belief that the adult brain is fixed. We now know that the brain changes throughout life in response to experience. This has fueled interest in cognitive enhancement. If the brain is malleable, can we train it to be smarter, faster, more creative? Commercial products promise to do exactly this. Brain-training games, nootropics, and neurostimulation devices flood the market. The science behind many of these claims is weak. Brain training often improves performance on the trained task but does not generalize. Nootropics have modest effects at best. Transcranial stimulation shows promise but carries risks. Beyond efficacy, there are ethical concerns. If cognitive enhancement works, who should have access? Will it exacerbate existing inequalities? The wealthy will enhance their children. The poor will fall further behind. There are also questions about authenticity. Is a chemically enhanced mind the same self? Does enhancement undermine the value of effort and achievement? The normative boundaries are unclear. Society has accepted some enhancements, such as education and caffeine. It rejects others, such as amphetamines for exam performance. Drawing these lines requires nuanced ethical reasoning. It requires considering not just individual choice but social consequences." },
  { id:"c2-21", level:"C2", title:"Discursive Formations in Machine-learned Corpora", text:"Foucault's archaeology of knowledge analyzed how statements are organized into discursive formations. These are systems of rules that determine what can be said within particular disciplines at particular times. Large language models present a new challenge. They are trained on vast corpora that span multiple discourses. They generate text by predicting the next token based on statistical patterns. Do they participate in discursive formations? Or do they transcend them? On one hand, language models reproduce the discourses in their training data. They can mimic the style of legal documents, scientific papers, or literary criticism. They operate within the constraints of language. On the other hand, they do not understand the rules that organize discourse. They do not know the difference between a scientific claim and a poetic metaphor. They mix genres promiscuously. This produces strange effects. A language model might generate text that sounds like philosophy but makes no argument. It might combine medical terminology with conspiracy theory. The concept of discursive formation assumes a human subject positioned within a social and institutional context. Language models lack this positioning. Yet their outputs enter and reshape discursive spaces. Understanding their role requires extending Foucauldian analysis beyond the human subject." },
  { id:"c2-22", level:"C2", title:"Thermodynamic Metaphors in Economic Theory", text:"Economics has long borrowed metaphors from physics. The concept of equilibrium comes directly from mechanics. Less recognized is the borrowing from thermodynamics. The idea that economies tend toward equilibrium resembles the concept of entropy. Just as gases diffuse to fill a container, markets are said to move toward balanced states. This metaphor has shaped economic thinking in profound ways. It suggests that intervention is unnecessary and perhaps harmful. The system will self-correct. But thermodynamic metaphors can be misleading. Economic systems are not closed systems. They are open, driven by energy flows, information, and human agency. Entropy in physics is well-defined. In economics, it is vague. Some economists use it to describe the dissipation of energy or the diffusion of knowledge. Others use it to critique growth. They argue that endless economic growth is impossible because it violates thermodynamic limits. These arguments are contested. The economy is not a physical system in any straightforward sense. Metaphors can illuminate. They can also obscure. The task is to use them critically, recognizing both their power and their limitations." },
  { id:"c2-23", level:"C2", title:"Geoengineering and the Anthropocenic Imaginary", text:"As climate change accelerates, geoengineering proposals have moved from science fiction to policy discussion. Solar radiation management would reflect sunlight back into space. Carbon dioxide removal would extract greenhouse gases from the atmosphere. These technologies promise to buy time. They also raise profound ethical and political questions. Who decides whether to deploy them? A single nation could unilaterally alter the global climate. The effects would be unevenly distributed. Some regions might benefit. Others might suffer. Geoengineering also risks moral hazard. If we believe technology can fix the climate, we might reduce efforts to cut emissions. The Anthropocenic imaginary shapes how we think about these options. It frames humans as planetary managers. We have caused the problem. We must now engineer the solution. This is a breathtaking shift in self-understanding. For most of history, humans saw themselves as subject to nature. Now we see ourselves as capable of redesigning it. Critics argue that this hubris is dangerous. They advocate for humility and adaptation. Supporters argue that the situation is too dire for purity. We must consider all options. The debate reflects deeper disagreements about humanity's place in the natural world." },
  { id:"c2-24", level:"C2", title:"Polyphonic Narratives in Transnational Literature", text:"Mikhail Bakhtin's concept of polyphony describes novels in which multiple independent voices coexist without being subordinated to a single authorial perspective. Transnational literature often exhibits this polyphony. Authors write from positions between cultures. Their texts incorporate multiple languages, histories, and narrative traditions. The result is a literature that resists easy categorization. It is neither fully of the homeland nor fully of the adopted country. It creates a third space. Polyphonic narration allows these texts to hold contradictions. Characters may speak different languages within the same novel. They may inhabit conflicting worldviews. The reader is not given a master key. They must navigate the multiplicity themselves. This formal complexity mirrors the experience of transnational subjects. Identity is not a fixed essence. It is a negotiation between competing affiliations. Transnational literature challenges nationalist literary canons. It insists that culture flows across borders. It is hybrid, creolized, and constantly evolving. Understanding this literature requires moving beyond monocultural frameworks. It requires appreciating the beauty of multiplicity." },
  { id:"c2-25", level:"C2", title:"The Crisis of Representation in Democratic Systems", text:"Representative democracy rests on the assumption that elected officials act on behalf of their constituents. This assumption is increasingly strained. Political parties have weakened. Voters are less loyal. Populist movements claim to represent the true will of the people against corrupt elites. Meanwhile, complex policy issues require expertise that most citizens lack. Climate policy, financial regulation, and public health cannot be decided by simple majority vote. This creates an epistemic problem. How can democratic representation combine popular legitimacy with competent governance? One response is deliberative democracy. Citizens are brought together in informed discussions. They weigh evidence and arguments. Their conclusions carry moral weight. Another response is sortition. Randomly selected citizens serve on policy panels. This avoids the distortions of electoral politics. Critics argue that these mechanisms are too slow and too small-scale. They cannot replace representative institutions. Perhaps the crisis of representation is not solvable by institutional design alone. It requires rebuilding trust. It requires a political culture that values truth and mutual respect. Without this cultural foundation, no institutional form can function." },
  { id:"c2-26", level:"C2", title:"Phenomenology and Algorithmic Mediation", text:"Phenomenology examines how we experience the world. It asks not what things are objectively, but how they appear to consciousness. Algorithmic mediation fundamentally alters this appearance. When we search for information, algorithms determine what we see. When we navigate cities, apps determine our routes. When we meet people, platforms suggest matches. These mediations are not neutral. They shape what is salient, what is accessible, what is thinkable. From a phenomenological perspective, algorithms are not merely tools. They are constitutive of our lifeworld. The lifeworld, in Husserl's terms, is the taken-for-granted background of experience. Algorithmic systems are becoming part of this background. We no longer notice their presence. We simply experience the world as filtered through them. This raises questions about authenticity. Is an experience still genuine if it is algorithmically curated? Phenomenology would resist framing this as a loss of authenticity. Experience is always mediated. But algorithmic mediation has distinctive features. It is opaque. It operates at scales beyond comprehension. It is driven by commercial interests. A phenomenological analysis of algorithmic life would attend to these specific modalities of appearance." },
  { id:"c2-27", level:"C2", title:"The Semantics of Silence", text:"Silence is not merely the absence of speech. It is a complex communicative phenomenon. Pragmatic theory distinguishes between different types of silence. There is the silence of inability, when words fail. There is the silence of refusal, when speech is withheld strategically. There is the silence of contemplation, when meaning is conveyed through presence rather than assertion. In high-context cultures, silence carries more information than in low-context cultures. Japanese communication, for example, values ma, the meaningful pause. Western communication often treats silence as awkward, something to be filled. The semantics of silence is also political. Whose voices are silenced? Official narratives exclude certain experiences. Marginalized groups are rendered invisible. Silence can be oppressive. But it can also be resistant. Strategic silence protects against surveillance. Collective silence in the face of injustice can be complicity. But collective silence in meditation can be solidarity. Understanding silence requires attention to context, power, and culture. It requires recognizing that meaning is not limited to what is said." },
  { id:"c2-28", level:"C2", title:"Metamodernism in Contemporary Culture", text:"Postmodernism taught us to be suspicious of grand narratives, sincerity, and truth claims. It celebrated irony, pastiche, and deconstruction. But in recent years, a new sensibility has emerged. Metamodernism describes a cultural posture that oscillates between modernist sincerity and postmodern irony. It is neither naive nor cynical. It acknowledges the constructed nature of meaning while still aspiring toward it. In cinema, directors like Wes Anderson create meticulously artificial worlds that nonetheless evoke genuine emotion. In literature, authors employ self-aware narration while telling heartfelt stories. In politics, movements combine memes and moral outrage. Metamodernism responds to a world that has seen through ideology but still needs hope. It recognizes that pure irony is exhausting. It leads to nihilism. But pure sincerity is no longer possible. We know too much about representation and power. The metamodern solution is to hold both in tension. To be sincere about the need for meaning while ironically aware of its impossibility. This oscillation is not a contradiction to be resolved. It is the defining structure of contemporary cultural experience." },
  { id:"c2-29", level:"C2", title:"CRISPR and the Dissolution of Species Boundaries", text:"The gene-editing technology CRISPR has made it possible to modify DNA with unprecedented precision. Scientists can correct genetic diseases. They can enhance crop resistance. They can even drive species to extinction by spreading infertility genes. The implications extend beyond medicine and agriculture. CRISPR dissolves the boundary between natural and artificial. An organism with edited genes is simultaneously natural and engineered. It challenges categories that have organized biology for centuries. Species, once seen as fixed, become fluid. The distinction between therapy and enhancement blurs. If we can eliminate sickle cell anemia, should we also enhance muscle growth? The teleological question is profound. Evolution has no goal. But gene editing introduces intentionality into the genome. We become designers of life. This power is not distributed equally. Wealthy nations and corporations control the technology. The gap between enhanced and unenhanced humans could widen. Some bioethicists call for a global moratorium on heritable editing. Others argue that the technology is too valuable to restrict. The dissolution of species boundaries is not merely a technical achievement. It is a philosophical event that demands new ethical frameworks." },
  { id:"c2-30", level:"C2", title:"Rhizomatic Knowledge in the Digital Age", text:"Gilles Deleuze and Felix Guattari contrasted rhizomatic and arborescent knowledge. Arborescent knowledge grows like a tree. It has a central trunk, branches, and roots. It is hierarchical and linear. Rhizomatic knowledge grows like a root system. It spreads horizontally. It has no center. Any point can connect to any other. The internet is often described as rhizomatic. Hyperlinks create non-hierarchical connections. Information flows in multiple directions. But the reality is more complex. Search engines create new hierarchies. Algorithms centralize attention. Platforms function as trunks from which content branches. The rhizomatic ideal is constantly compromised by capitalist enclosure. Open knowledge commons are privatized. Data is extracted and monetized. Yet rhizomatic practices persist. Wikipedia is edited by thousands without central control. Open-source software develops through decentralized collaboration. Peer-to-peer networks bypass institutional gatekeepers. The tension between rhizomatic potential and arborescent capture defines the digital age. A truly rhizomatic knowledge system would resist commodification. It would value multiplicity over consensus. It would recognize that there is no single correct map of knowledge. Creating such a system requires both technical architecture and political will." }
];